Essay: I had to speak with someone about missing work often and gave them their "last chance". It was empowering, but I felt really bad because I was able to put myself in their shoes. The look on their face was absolutely horrifying to me.
Deb1: See how people make decisions based on their personality in a leadership role?
Deb2: No

Essay: I remember when I was employed at Walmart and my manager had power over me. He would tell me what to do and how to act and when I could take my breaks. I resented him because he was not very nice. I was never allowed to do anything fun while on the job.
Deb1: I think that the purpose was to give others raffle tickets for the prize
Deb2: I do not think the essay I wrote affected my answers to any of the questions

Essay: I felt very responsible. I felt a lot of pressure. I did not feel near as in control as one would expect. It was very uncomfortable and unpleasant.
Deb1: How people judge others based on their own feelings of, or lack thereof, power.
Deb2: Possibly, but I'm really not sure.

Essay: A time when someone had power over me was my last employer. She had the power to take away my job and used that power to her advantage. I felt like I was irritated and wanted to quit because I don't think anyone has control over me and whoever feels like they do I do not want to be associated with.
Deb1: To see how many people are considerate towards others
Deb2: no

Essay: I had power to continue a relationship or ended. I was in a position to end my long time romantic relationship and move out of state. The person I was with was begging me to stay and willing to make a lot of changes to keep me there. I felt torn. I decided to stay with them.
Deb1: To understand how people judge each other
Deb2: I don't think it effected my answers because I really didn't think about the essay when I was answering.

Essay: As a former teacher, I had power like this almost everyday. I would evaluate students' knowledge and whether or not they were ready to continue through school. It was nerve-wracking to have to make those decisions. I always felt there was something else I should offer the students. I never felt good about the power.
Deb1: How power may affect one's decision to trust another.
Deb2: Not really.

Essay: A coworker was new here and I trained them to be under me and help with my job and daily tasks. After a year, they had sucked up to the higher-ups so much that they ended up with a higher role than I have. I have asked if I could get a higher role too and now she controls whether I do or not.
Deb1: how trusting and giving to a stranger makes you feel
Deb2: not really, maybe made me a bit angry but didn't affect my choice

Essay: I had an account where I made a percentage of the increase and profits every year. And one year before I got paid it increased so much that it got turned into a house account and I wasnt going to get paid on it going forward. I felt like I was betrayed and back stabbed by the company. I was very angry and felt revengeful and wanted to find another job.
Deb1: how peoples experiences envoke their emotions in their current state when thinking about them
Deb2: yes, I think it mad me more emotional and angry than normal

Essay: When I interviewed for Walls Fargo. I felt confident, but less professional than they were. I did two individual interviews and then an interview with both people. I was feeling very worn out by the end of the day.
Deb1: The willingness to give items in return. The ability to read faces or not.
Deb2: no
Deb3: Odd make up of random questions.

Essay: My employer illegally changed the vacation payout policy and I can call and report them to the Department of Labor and get them into trouble, causing problems for the HR department. I feel angry and vindictive and want to cause them trouble since they cheated me out of money.
Deb1: How people interpret faces/emotions.
Deb2: I don't think so.

Essay: I was working as a shift manager when one of my employees Jeanette asked me to put in a good word to get her a raise. Jeanette was a hard worker and truly deserved a raise. I went to my general manager and explained to him that she was a very hard worker and always completed her tasks on time and always went above and beyond. He seemed hesitant to give her a raise due to her having an issue with tardiness. I explained to him that she takes care of her younger siblings and when she has to take them to school she has to rush to work. After a few more minutes of discussion I convinced him to give her the raise. I felt empowered and proud for both myself and for Jeanette. She ended up getting more of a raise than she expected.
Deb1: I think the purpose of this study is to see how generous we are as people. Also to see how we react when we receive power. I was given the power to give raffle tickets to the other survey participant.
Deb2: Yes, it boosted my mood. It brought me into a happy place from remembering helping out my friend. It caused me to be happier for the rest of the study.

Essay: I was letting my students study and they got loud and disruptive. I gave them a warning about being too loud and that they would lose the ability to enjoy this down time if they were being disrespectful to the others. I felt like I had to be the bad guy, but the power of my authority and how quickly they responded was impressive. I feel like my students do listen to me.
Deb1: how thoughtful people are of others
Deb2: no

Essay: My boss had power over me by being able to decide whether I got a raise or not.
Deb1: None
Deb2: No

Essay: The moment I recalled was when I had my first job in highschool so around 40 years ago. I was working in a bowling ally and had to get the pins and set them back up everytime. My boss was this man who had a grouchy and unusual additude. He controlled my life it seemed, I was always called in to work and if I did not come in I would not get payed. I spent hours working instead of studying or with my friends because I did not have the courage to say no.
Deb1: I think the purpose of this survey is about seeing how well people do in other circumstances or unusual circumstances and how empathetic people are.
Deb2: I do think it effected some of my answers because it made me recall some of the hardships I had to go through

Essay: I used to be a direct supervisor over 10 employees.  I had power over everything about their jobs: starting pay, raises, evaluations, time off, etc.  In a specific situation I found out that an employee was stealing lunches from other employees.  I initially felt sad for the employee who was stealing as it was obvious that she had issues outside of lunch and food.  Due to the theft, I had to fire her.  When I brought her to my office to discuss the issue, I felt sadness for her, anger that it had happened, and relief that the situation would be over soon.
Deb1: I think the purpose of this study is to evaluate people's perceptions of other people based on their feelings about trust.
Deb2: No, I do not think it had any effect on the answers I had.

Essay: I was in the mental treatment center because I had suicidal thoughts the day before. I no longer felt that way and wanted to be released. The head doctor talked with me about it and refused to let me go. I felt very angry and trapped.
Deb1: The purpose was to see how creative I can write and if I read instructions thoroughly.
Deb2: No.

Essay: Running for student government 13years ago when I was in 11th grade. My obtaining the spot of class secretary kept several others from winning. I seen people look scared and turned red when I gave my awesome speech. I felt pretty good because I was anti the norm at the time.
Deb1: perceptions...biases.
Deb2: It helped me to picture faces and Identify the emotion attached to said faces.

Essay: The situation that came to mind when someone had power over me was when I was reprimanded for a job I did incorrectly at work. I remember that his face got a deeper shade of red and he seemed to get taller even though I know that isnt possible. I remember feeling slightly helpless and only being able to sit there and get yelled at. Afterwards I made sure that I never made that mistake again.
Deb1: I think the purpose of this study was to see how we percieve human emotions through body language
Deb2: I think it put me in the frame of mind to look further into body language
Deb3: No, Thank you for the survey

Essay: I was able to give orders to people - felt good to be in control and power, telling others what to do. I told them how to properly dissect the body and was able to point out all parts of the anatomy.
Deb1: How well we can see emotion on others faces
Deb2: No

Essay: I walked a fellow coworker through a difficult task.  We answered each others questions and I was finally able to lead him in the right direction.  I felt smart, empowered, happy.
Deb1: Comparing how somebody currently feels to how they perceive how others feel
Deb2: no i do not

Essay: I was NCOIC of my section, and one of my soldiers failed to show up on time for work. I had been dealing a lot with this soldier and his personal life so i was well aware of why he was late, but that did not excuse his behaviors. I was forced to inflict on him corrective action in the form of physical exercise, and time (staying after release) I felt bad for the guy, I really did not want to because i knew what was happening in his home life, but it was the right thing to do so I did what i had to and ended up building an even stronger repor because he trusted me to help him not just punish
Deb1: To see if we have racial bias based on actions and predisposition of images and feelings related to those images
Deb2: not really, although the person was of a different nationality and religious persuasion

Essay: I was with friends looking at a car. Sue a fat red head iwth green eyes and messed up teeth, kept talkig so I could not think. I was staying ith her she forced me to go, then left me without a ride so I had to buy it.
Deb1: to determine how people react to certain scenarios
Deb2: no

Essay: I had an issue with the last company I worked for.  I felt like my manager had complete control over me, my family, my well being, and everything else that can be related to a job.  I hated the feeling.  I hated feeling like one person could completely ruin me.  In the end that is exactly what happened.  I screwed up and they chose to suspend me for almost 3 weeks and then they fired me.  I was held in limbo that whole time.  It was terrible and I don't ever want to feel like that again.  Once I become employed again I plan on making sure that I make choices that allow me to  feel secure if something does happen with my new job.
Deb1: I feel it was to people peoples perception of themselves and others.
Deb2: No it didn't because I have had some good things happen in my life lately so that could not hold me back.

Essay: My boss and owner of the company were upset over my performance on a project so they demoted me. I felt humiliated, ashamed and resentful. I was also very embarrassed and felt like I couldn't tell anyone close to me what happened. I had no control over it.
Deb1: How a stressful situation effects our choices.
Deb2: I think that was the plan of your study, to have the essay effect the answers given.

Essay: I was a high school teacher teaching an English class and I had power over my students.  The lesson was on the book Lord of the Flies and we were reading a chapter out loud.  I had power in the sense that the students had to be on good behavior while this activity was proceeding.  If they were talking or distracting other students I had the power to tell them to stop their action, and if they chose not to I had the power to carry out consequences (e.g sit outside, take away points, call their parents, etc.)  I felt a great sense of responsibility because there were about 20 individuals I had control over.  Also because they were children I felt how I used my power over them would have a great effect on them.
Deb1: To determine if there is any correlation between how a person perceives power and their degree of generosity.  If so, how?
Deb2: Yes because to brainstorm for the essay I had to put myself in other people's shoes and think about their point of views and how they perceived me.  Writing the essay probably made me feel more emphatic toward other people.

Essay: I was a supervisor for an archaeological field school, and oversaw the work of several college students as they excavated. I was about the same age as them, and it could be difficult at times to get them to respect my authority. It felt good to be in a position of power, because I was able to oversee excavations and feel as though all of my training was put to good use. However, it could be frustrating when students would question my authority because they felt that they knew best even though I had far more experience. In those cases, I would just explain to them the reasons behind my choices and decisions, and they would eventually acquiesce. Once I had convinced them, it felt good to be seen as an authoritative figure.
Deb1: To determine how empathetic people are as well as what their political views and personal values are. Perhaps this is to determine whether empathy and the ability to read other's emotions are correlated with peoples values and politics.
Deb2: I don't think that it affected the answers to my questions, because I don't feel as though the situation I described was similar to any of the questions asked.

Essay: One situation where someone had power over me was during a recent interview. The person interviewing me had the ability to approve or deny my application to work somewhere for a summer, and this job would play a large part in my future. It was incredibly overwhelming and intimidating. I sat down at a table with this person on the other end, as they slowly evaluated my resume. I was then asked every question imaginable about my resume, including some I never would have expected. I had to sit there in an uncomfortable chair and try to think of a response that would both answer and put me in a good light. This person would not only choose if I would be part of the program but who I would be paired with, and who I would ultimately learn from. I was sweating and I am sure my face was bright way as I tried to remain calm and convince this person that I was a good candidate.
Deb1: To see how mood can impact how you view people / things. How tired you are impacts how clearly you can identify another person's emotions. Not really sure!
Deb2: No I don't think so. I tried to answer each part of the survey individually.

Essay: I time in which i had power was when i was a supervisor at my old job. I was in charge of many individuals, one however never listened and did what was asked of them. This made me angry when they woildnt do the job request and required of them.
Deb1: Human behavior and beliefs
Deb2: No

Essay: First professional-level job evaluation.  Terror is the only way I could describe it. It turned out I got a raise on the spot and the only criticism the boss had was I sometimes worked so fast it made her look bad.
Deb1: Perception of others and their actions or possible actions.
Deb2: No, it didn't seem all that related.

Essay: My former fiance held power over me on many occasions. Unfortunately he was emotionally abusive ans a compulsive gambler. On one particular occasion he had just "won" $12,000. My brother-in-law's brother was in the hospital in Texas. We lived in Las Vegas. The probability was very high that he would mot make it out of the hospital (he needed a heart and lung transplant). I asked for a couple hundred bucks to fly home and see him. I was told no since it would just be a waste of money. I was so very angry I wanted to smash his head into the machine he was playing.
Deb1: Perceptions of others based on visual and verbal cues.
Deb2: No effct

Essay: I was talking with one of my bosses regarding some complaints that some employees (and I) had recently in our office. We hadn't gotten raises or our usual bonuses in over a year at that point so we were talking trying to find a middle ground where everyone would be happy. I was terrified - very nervous, as I don't like any type of confrontation, and this particular boss was known to be a bit dramatic at times. We talked for a long time, and she finally agreed to speak to our overarching supervisor, who was the owner/CEO and really in charge of what was going on. But having to act as the intermediary for everyone made me feel very awkward and uncomfortable, especially as we ha really no leverage - we couldn't all quit, we needed jobs!
Deb1: To test whether a person's feeling of powerlessness would affect the amount given away to a stranger.
Deb2: It might have - it put me in a frame of mind where I wasn't feeling particularly generous, just nervous.
Deb3: Nothing I can think of at this time!

Essay: I was trying to fly out of China but the authorities were saying my visa was not valid. There was nobody that I could talk to. The answer was simply no. I felt angry at my inability to do anything about it. I felt angry at the person for not doing more to try and be understanding. I knew that it was his job, and if he tried to move further up the ladder he would be told the same thing he is telling me. I felt like there was nothing I could do, and I gave up and accepted my situation fairly quickly.
Deb1: To figure out how a person's emotions change when they are in or out of a position of power.  Describe how empathetic people are after feeling these emotions. Describe how much somebody would want to share after these emotions.
Deb2: No, I tried to stay objective and take my previous experiences out of it.

Essay: A couple of years ago I worked at a summer camp in Maine. I was in charge of teaching a variety of classes, one of which was stained glass making. Part of the process of making stained glass is soldering various pieces together. One week I had a girl who just would not listen. She'd mess around with sharp glass, try to take her shoes off, be careless with the soldering iron, and finally I had enough. I kicked her out, then marched her down to the office where I pulled the camp directer aside and demanded that she be kicked out of the camp. She agreed with me, and I never had to deal with that particular child again.
Deb1: Research about trust in various situations?
Deb2: Possibly. It may have skewed my perspective and made me answer the questions regarding power more positively.

Essay: It was initially during my time with Toys R US after I was transferred.  The boss and I were talking.  I explained that I was a new manager and that I would need help adjusting into the role.  She explained what was expected of me and that it was up to me to drive the results of what she wanted.  In that instance I felt very helpless as I did not know how to drive these results aside from personally achieving them myself.
Deb1: How well moods can be read based on eyes
Deb2: It put me into a mindset reflecting on the situation and how helpless I felt at the time.

Essay: Being a team leader, I was in charge of 2 soldiers. A lot of soldiers are hungry for power. I, on the other hand, never wanted it. I don't like bossing people around.
Deb1: To see if we were paying attention. That's why you threw in a question to test us to see if we were actually paying attention.
Deb2: No, I don't think it affected the answers at all.
Deb3: Yes, I want to know what "other" did with the 3000 raffle tickets.

Essay: I was having a job interview for a new position at work. I was already pretty nervous as it would have been a huge change for me and my family.   /  / I went into the interview room and one of the managers Liz who I already did get along with was the main interviewer, I was pretty angry at that point as I thought it showed bias towards another candidate. I remember her stupid curly hair that she had at the time and this stupid little smirk she had on her face everytime she threw a random, tough questions my way.
Deb1: I think the study was about trust and how humans react to strangers.
Deb2: No, I don't think it did.
Deb3: Great study, well put together and easy to follow!

Essay: I was a volunteer at a high school for the band. I had to look out for mistakes they were making and help them correct them. It was an odd feeling to feel like I had that kind of control over people because I had never had it before. I would have to correct the way they marched or when it came to Clarinets I would have to make sure they knew how to play their music.
Deb1: To see how I feel after recalling an experience where I had power over someone and how that may influence my decisions.
Deb2: No
Deb3: The questions seemed unrelated to the writing task, but I'm sure they had meaning.

Essay: I once had the power to help my friend to obtain a job where I worked. It was up to me to help her get hired on so the fate of her employment was initially in my hands. She was very anxious and excited. I felt nervous for her as well because I hoped she would get hired on.
Deb1: I think the study was about remembering past feelings and emotions, interpreting facial expressions and generosity.
Deb2: I felt good about my essay so I may have been in a more positive mood.
Deb3: I think this was a great and interesting study.

Essay: The incident I think about was at a antiques show. I saw something I wanted at one exhibition that I felt I could make some money on as a dealer. The dealer who was running the booth that had the item I wanted saw that I really liked it, and I could tell that he realized he had power over me as to the price he would sell the item to me. Prices are usually pretty variable at an antiques show. And I was in the position where I felt I had no control over the situation, except of course to turn down the item if I didn't want to pay what the dealer priced it at. I tried to be passive as I could, both not to show my keen interest, although from my looking at the item the prospective seller knew I wanted it. I had a special interest in the item not only because I could make a good profit, but also because it was a good item for me to be handling for the sake of image and my marketing in the field. In the end, I did not barter, and purchased the item at the higher price the dealer asked for it in realizing I had no power in the situation.
Deb1: I think the purpose of the study was to get information on how an individual makes choices and also positions himself with respect to other individuals and within society on the basis of how he assesses others (as in the test of trying to read the persons' eyes) and also reflects on himself in simple ways as prompted by parts of the survey.
Deb2: I don't think the brief essay I wrote affected my answers except to the degree that it got my mind working to be alert for the following part of the survey. In most situations, I recognize the power dynamics, and take them as fact and for granted so I am usually at most minimally affected by them emotionally or in behaving in the situation.

Essay: I was at the mercy of the interviewer - i felt hopeless and powerless and I just did what i could to try and please her
Deb1: Perceptions of others
Deb2: No

Essay: I had to terminate an employee for drinking on the job and always being consistently late.  I brought him into the office and explained to him the issues we were having with his work ethics and poor choices he made while at work.  After a few minutes of this I told him we had to let him go.  I didn't feel too terribly bad about this decision because he was putting others at risk and didn't seem to care.  I still don't regret my decision.
Deb1: I believe it has something to do with decision making.  Taking into account perceptions and ability to trust others.
Deb2: I do not think it had an affect on my answers.

Essay: The situation I envisioned was a time two years ago when I was at the final exam session for a class I was taking. We were supposed to present our research for a paper we had been working on all semester. Our professor also wanted us to engage with each other about other people's research. I was very anxious about talking in front of everyone and so I did not want to ask anyone questions about their research, although the professor kept hinting that how much we engaged with others would effect our grade. I know he was mostly talking to me, because I had said nothing aside from explaining my own research topic. I felt very anxious about talking, but also nervous that the professor would take off points for not asking questions.

I was working in a tire warehouse.I was the manager. I wanted to be lazy that day. So I made mike unload the tire truck as i just sat. second i made SAM and hector load trucks as i continued to sit. I would have Adam do all the paperwork. I made all these situation seem like a training exercise when really i was being lazy. The look on mikes face was anger. the look on SAM and hectors faces was disgust. as for Adam has face looked confused but even with all that I got what I wanted. To be lazy and get paid for it. when I look back on it I was a asshole for that and I feel bad now.
Deb1: The purpose is to see about people emotions

Essay: When I first applied for my visa to enter the United States, I had to go for an interview at the US Embassy. I knew the person I was meeting with had the power to grant or deny my ability to come to the USA. The situation was extremely nerve-wracking for me, given the harsh reputation that visa officials have. Even though I consider myself an upstanding citizen, I was still sweating nervously and having negative thoughts right up until the interview. I felt very nervous, questioning why I was putting myself through that.
Deb1: Perceptions of people's eyes when feeling nervous.
Deb2: It put me in a somewhat nervous piece of mind.

Essay: A few summers ago. I was working for an elderly woman. My job was to assist her in her daily basic needs such as bathing, dressing, running errands, cooking, and cleaning. She also had a son present in the home. When working I understood that I would only be working for her. Shortly, her son became involved and began to have me do small jobs around the house for him such as wash clothes, iron clothes, etc. I felt that he had power over me because I worked for his mother in their home and he knew how important my job was to me and that I would not decline his wishes. I felt like I was being used and was powerless. It made me feel uncomfortable and made my job unjoyable.
Deb1: I believe the purpose of this study is to write about a experience when someone made you feel powerless. In addition decision making and personal beliefs.
Deb2: I honestly do not belive the essay I wrote had any relation to the questions in the study.

Essay: I was called out at work by one of my managers. It turned out to be a misunderstanding, but they were concerned with my lack of production. I could have easily lost my job if they didn't understand it from my point of view.
Deb1: Connecting my level of being dominated and my feelings toward society and my income level
Deb2: No

Essay: When I was 17, I went to a party with some friends. The host of the party was named Clay. He was 6' 1" with gorgeous brown eyes that you could melt in and nice tan skin. He told me he thought I was cute and we went to go make out upstairs. He started taking off his shirt, it was a blue button down with pearl snaps so it wasn't hard to take off. He tried taking my clothes off and I refused and he started hitting me. The music downstairs was so loud that no one could hear what was going on. He kept punching me and saying I should be lucky because not everyone would find me so attractive, especially now. He tore my shorts and he raped me in his bed. As he raped me, he punched me until I was unconscious. I passed out and woke up the next morning alone and wrapped in a grey blanket. I felt broken and confused at the time, but now I just feel hatred towards him.
Deb1: Our perceptions towards other people based on previous experiences we've had with people, and how much we are willing to trust other people.

The regional manager first entered my manager's office, chatted with her, and came out to evaluate me after about 10 minutes in the office. The man was in his mid-fifties. He was balding, but still had a good amount of dark brown hair. He work glasses and had on a nice looking gray suit. I tried to work even faster than my usual pace of work because I wanted to show him that I was speedy, yet efficient. At one point, he would stand behind my back and looked over my shoulder to observe what I was doing. Time felt like it stood still, but he finally left. Essay: As I held the spoon in front of my baby's face, I could see the excitement well up in her eyes. She squealed with anticipation! She adores apples and could not wait to get a taste. The longer I took to feed her, the more anxious she got. I felt so rushed but so happy she enjoys her meal so much.
Deb1: Probably to see how generous people are and what people think of other demographics based on their socioeconomic status.
Deb2: It probably made me think more about the questions.

Essay: I had a bad reaction to a medication and I was in the hospital. A doctor was analyzing my situation to determine what type of medication to put me on. The doctor's eyes revealed he was concerned. He asked me many questions. I felt powerless. I tried to answer the questions the best I could under the circumstances. I didn't know if he would be able to help me or not.
Deb1: Views on political and social ideas. Also How a person feels when they are under someone elses authority.
Deb2: It helped me to be more aware of my feelings.
Deb3: Thank you and no other comments.

Essay: At my work I have control over making decisions for clients. I had a situation in which I had to make a decision whether to over ride our rules to make a customer happy/ I knew if I did this I would be risking my job but the potential of making a good commission on it. I did what was right and did not make the customer happy.
Deb1: to analyze our perceptions of people.
Deb2: no.

Essay: It was a personal romantic situation. I didn't realize you would ask me to describe it. I thought about lying but whatever. It made me feel strong. Big. Sometimes its fun to be in charge
Deb1: I think maybe you wanted me to feel powerful and maybe I would feel the peoples eyes weren't powerful. I'm really not sure though
Deb2: I kind of feel like writing made me feel less powerful. I felt most powerful during the visualization part

Essay: I am thinking of a situation in which I challenged my boss at my company. He had made a mistake, yet he was blaming the mistake on me. I tried to challenge him but he used his superior authority to thwart me. I remember him looking at me like I was subordinate, stupid and inexperienced, yet I knew I was right. It was incredibly frustatrating to have no control over the situation.
Deb1: To show how thinking about a time when we are powerless wants us to empower others (e.g., share the raffle tickets).
Deb2: I think it may have had some affect, making me more likely to say that I see things from the  other person's perspective.

Essay: My last annual evaluation was very traumatic.  I was required to take a math exam to continue in the Pharmacy Tech position I had held in this hospital for 10 years.  I had taken one each year for several years.  Passing it was now a requirement to remain employed.  I knew I did not do well in the exam.....I was very nervous.  My boss was trying very hard to be nice to me about this, but he was unhappy with me...I could tell.  I was passed retirement age but really needed the extra income that this position gave me.  He kept trying to help me understand the formula concepts that I had failed on the test and the more he tried, the more I felt sad, nervous, embarrassed, you name it; I felt it!  Finally, he just came out and told me that we had to change my position to something clerical and to try to find a job for me there at lower pay, of course.  What could I do but agree?  I felt really "down" for several days.  I had worked there for a long time.  I think the term is "dread"....I felt a deep dread of what I needed to do.  It was not long after that I decided to retire completely...and I did.
Deb1: Perceptions of emotions and how we read them;  our ability to describe emotions in writing; how we reason on sharing vs winning.
Deb2: Yes.  It set the mood for the answers to the following questions.  In fact, it seemed to cause my answers to be more negative than I may have otherwise felt.

Essay: As someone who has been in different managing positions, I have been in many situations where I have had power over other employees. Power makes people feel important, it makes people feel respected, and it's something a lot of people unknowingly get obsessed with in my opinion. The time I was thinking about particularly is when I was first asked by an employee about changing their schedule as there was a mistake. He was new, he was scared. He was so scared to just confront me about the problem, and I could tell in that moment how much power I had. It felt strange. I could've told him anything and he would've bought it. His hands constantly moving, eyes never making contact with mine.
Deb1: How people interact with others based on power/trust/thoughts
Deb2: I don't think it had too much of an effect. Seeing as I'm in a much different position in my life currently and many of the questions asked for how I'm feeling in this moment, compared to when the story was told.

Essay: I have power at work to provide credits for classes that I teach to students who attend training's. I feel powerful and respected. I also sometimes feel worried that one of the students will fail and it will be my fault for not doing the best I could to help them learn the materials.
Deb1: Creativity and generosity.
Deb2: No, I think the essay got my brain working and helped me come up with better answers for the tire and pencil questions.

Essay: The time that sticks out most was an abusive boyfriend who decided to throw me out of the house at night with only a night gown on because he was mad. I was scared and freezing cold. Snow and below freezing temps and I was on the porch. It's funny that I was not mad and just kind of sat there. In shock or just not wanting to fight anymore, I just waited. That's probably why he let me back in. Can I still picture his face? You bet I can all the way down to the color of his eyes
Deb1: How a person feels after remembering an unhappy experience.
Deb2: Somehow I think it made me sad enough to be lazy. It was like remembering it made me just give up again. Maybe I want to change how I handled it?
Deb3: It was interesting to think of something that happened so long ago.

Essay: My 7 year old wanted to take the new basketball he got for Christmas to school this morning.  I explained to him that he could take the basketball only if he completed all of his required tasks, brushing his teeth, making his bed, clearing the breakfast dishes, getting his clothes on (without argument).  He did not complete the entire list, but he was working very hard to do so.  He really wanted to take the basketball to school.  I had the power to tell him he could not because he did not finish all of tasks, but I let him take it anyway, simply because he tried his hardest to get the jobs done.
Deb1: To see how generous people are (or are not) after feeling they have been exposed to a situation in which they have the power over someone else.
Deb2: No, I do not feel that the essay I wrote affected my answers to any of the questions in the study.  I would have given 50% of my tickets in any event.
Deb3: It would be interesting to know how much the "Other" donated.

Essay: I was assistant manager at a retail store and delegated tasks to employees. I told a few employees to take clothes out to the sale floor for replenishment. I felt in control and like I was doing my job accordingly.
Deb1: Feeling of excitement after the possibility of winning a bonus has been given.
Deb2: No. I explained a job that I had and was just described performing the duties of that job in particular moment

Essay: It was a work situation.  I was the manager of the department and I had a worker who was excellent.  I was responsible for his promotion, or not, in the department.  We had a conversation about the possibilities of him advancing to another level.  I felt good that I was able to offer him the position of supervisor.
Deb1: Perhaps how different people perceive power, what they would do with power, if they like or dislike power etc vs their perceived social status?
Deb2: No

Essay: I was the supervisor of an intern at my company. When she came, she gave a lot of suggestions to our product (an online software) which basically requires us to redesign the whole product. I felt a little upset because she haven't get very familiar with the product yet. So I had to explain to her that she needs to get to know the product first and try to get involved in our workflow first before giving too many suggestions. I was not super upset because this happens to many new workers who just came out of school.
Deb1: Maybe trying to find the relationship between trust and political view.
Deb2: Maybe made me a little more serious in answering the following questions.
Deb3: Nope. You should not pay only $2 for such as big study. It worth $5 at least.

Essay: I went to the police academy for a short amount of time. That's where I learned I wasn't good with authority figures who had power over me and used it against me for no good reason. Getting yelled at and abused for no reason, and even seeing them find a reason just because was no fun. I felt really angry and downtrodden.
Deb1: I think the purpose of the study was to see how people react to pictures of others when they are feeling certain ways.
Deb2: No

Essay: While I do not frequently have positions of power over other people, I do remember an incident when I was working as a teacher abroad in which I called out two students for cheating during a big examination. The two girls knew that they had done something wrong, and while they tried to make an excuse, they were 100% guilty and knew it. I felt horrible for having to punish them, but I also felt like they deserved it and should suffer for trying to gain an advantage over the other students.
Deb1: To study empathy and power dynamics
Deb2: I don't think so--I tend to keep memories fairly separate from present tasks.

Essay: I had messed up on a project at work I tried to cover it up without noticing my supervisor.  My coworker was aware I messed up and use the information to get me to do some of their work for them.
Deb1: Understand how people perceive themselves.
Deb2: No.

Essay: I worked as a paramedic for close to 10 years, during this time I have had to deal with different personalities. Some of the personalities are nicer than others. I had a patient who was in danger of hurting themselves and others. He was under the influence of drugs and I needed him to be calm and ride with me to the hospital. I was in control because he had to go to the hospital. I remained in control and convinced him to put his clothes on, sit nicely, and even talk to me on the way to the hospital without the need of restraints (physical or chemical). I was please with how that call went and happy, I didn't need to use anything invasive. The only rush I get from being in that situation is knowing I did the right thing for another human being, no matter what the problem is.
Deb1: I think the purpose of the study was to investigate one's personal capacity for empathy and see whether that correlates to demographic information such as income/education/race/political orientation/etc.
Deb2: I don't think that it affected my answers.
Deb3: Enjoyed thinking through the raffle part.

Essay: my girlfriend wanted me to loan her 5000 dollars for a new car. i felt i had the advantage over her because she really needed the money
Deb1: comprehention of story
Deb2: no

Essay: I felt very bad. This was my worst feeling​ in my wife. Real disaster
Deb1: IDK
Deb2: no

Essay: When I was in college, I worked for an extremely unpleasant man who was part owner of the deli where I was employed part-time.  He had a temper and I was unnecessarily berated numerous times for minor mistakes.  He was also known for making sexually suggestive comments to female employees.  I felt very helpless because I needed the job.  I was very uncomfortable working when he was there, because I never knew what his mood would be or what he might say.
Deb1: I think the purpose of this study is to see how well we are able to identify what other people are thinking or feeling in different situations based on how well we know them.
Deb2: No, I don't project that experience with that one person onto other people.

Essay: This was during an interview for a job.  I wanted this job very much.  The person interviewing me was a investment advisor.  He had brown eyes and was quite bald.  Although he was quite friendly at the time, I would learn later that he was a gigantic prick.  But then, I thought I wanted that job and I did my best to make a good impression and get the job, which I did.  I felt nervous but not too nervous.

Deb2: No.  none.  N/A

Essay: Going on a date with a guy from an online dating website. I already knew this guy was infatuated with me from our conversation online so in person on our date I could enjoy holding all the power. I felt more confident, more charismatic, interesting, and kind of unstoppable.. almost dangerous. It was exciting and fun, and I kind of took a mental step back from the date just to observe his reactions to things I said or did. Kind of like a cat toying with a mouse. I felt like it was more of an amusing game than a legitimate date.
Deb1: Test the effects of feeling powerful or envisioning feeling powerful on thought process
Deb2: Yes, before the first question I was ready to fall asleep (been awake for over 24 hrs now) but when the test asked me about wanting to sleep I realized I was full of energy again

Essay: At dinner, my daughter wanted another tortilla shell, and we only had 2 per person, she already ate her two, but was begging to get more.  Then she tried to eat her fathers.  I kept telling her, she already had her two, and I kept trying to distract her to get her to eat something else.  I felt bad that she wasn't able to get what she wants, but at the same time, I was getting frustrated as well.  She wasn't listening and she was being persistent, then she started hitting and kicking to get her way, so I had to sit on the floor with her and wrap my arms and legs around her to calm her down.  I had to keep calm, even though I wanted to scream at her for her behavior.  It's hard to stay calm when someone else is spiraling out of control.  Eventually I got her to calm down and she decided a good compromise was sitting on my lap to eat, and have some steak.  I was exhausted by the end of the ordeal.
Deb1: how much certain kind of people perceive and trust others
Deb2: I don't think it did, but if it did have an impact, it put me in more of a funky mood before beginning

Essay: I had the responsibility of being in charge while the supervisor was out sick. When notifying my coworkers of the situation they were very angry. Usually because the one was always in charge. She moped around all day and was not very productive. I felt awful that she was so resentful but also angry about her snide remarks.
Deb1: I think this survey is about getting us to perceive where we picture ourselves in life and how we mix with other people.
Deb2: I do not believe it affected the questions I was asked.

Essay: I was working in Insurance Sales and as a sales producer with the ability to discern and decide on underwriting risks within certain categories.  I was evaluating a policy I could write for a family that had had a number of losses within a short span of time across multiple lines of insurance.  I decided not to take on the risk, as their risk patterns, while technically within our company guidelines, showed too much risk as a whole spectrum and would not be acceptable across the spectrum for the company.  I remember speaking with them in person about this and they seemed disappointed.  I felt bad for them, but ultimately knew that they would be able to find insurance elsewhere and that I had to do what was best for our agency and customer base as a whole.  Ultimately, reflecting on it, I felt power over a couple who was 20 years my senior, but also felt guilt that I didn't want to provide them insurance because of the risk they presented.  However, end of the day, I know I made the right choice.
Deb1: To determine facial cues, namely in the eyes, following a series of questions designed to get a sense for empathy and personality in the participant.
Deb2: Yes, I think that it put me in a mindset where I was thinking about the attitudes and perceptions of others and pre-empted me to feel more emphatically for others.

Essay: Many years ago I was taking a nursing test. Blood pressure. Simple. Too anxious. 3 nurses watching your every move. Couldn't hear anything in the stethescope. Couldn't really remember how to count or read a watch anymore. These were very nice caring ladies that turned into the scariest people in the world. I felt that I needed to apologize for existing. I failed.
Deb1: to test your assumptions about other people.
Deb2: Perhaps a little.  The essay was not very pleasant.

Essay: I was a lifeguard performing a double save. The instant I saw both go down, I instinctively whistled and then jumped into the water. I immediately knew what I needed to do and did it to perfection. After I successfully rescued them, I felt unstoppable.
Deb1: How much people trust things.
Deb2: No. It was just to get me riled up.

Essay: While attending community college, I was hired as the editor of the campus newspaper. The teacher of the journalism courses was in charge of the newspaper. Her name was Teri Maddox. I applied for the position so that I could write my own column. Other duties the editor performed was editing the content of the newspaper. But every time I would perform this duty, Teri would come behind me and do it all over again and make whatever changes she wanted. She edited my column as well and really had all the power of the newspaper. One day, it became necessary to fire one of the reporters. She insisted that I do it, even thought in all reality I had no power. It seemed like she really wanted to control everything but give me the dirty work to do. I got mad because she took control of everything else I was supposed to do, but said it was entirely my responsibility to fire this person. We ended up doing it together and soon after, I quit the position.
Deb1: I'm not sure. I guess it would be accessing my personality type first, then accessing how I interpret other people's facial expressions.
Deb2: I think it probably did. Well it put me in a slightly negative mood remembering a time I was under someone's thumb.

Essay: I could make a decision for someone else and they had no say in it. I felt anxious that my decision would cause them undue suffering, but was confident I knew what was needed to be done
Deb1: Unsure, trust in others
Deb2: no

Essay: I was a supervisor delivering evaluations for my shift of three people and my evaluation weighed heavily on whether they received a raise or not. The evaluations all went well but there were times that I was a bit nervous as to what their reactions would be when receiving their performance reviews.
Deb1: To determine how well you can read someone by the look in their eyes.
Deb2: No

Essay: A former manager was preventing me from leaving his department for a better job in a different location.  In one of those sitcom, one-in-a-million chances, I was at the wrong place at the wrong time, and heard him having a conversation about me around a corner telling another manager about it.  I felt so betrayed and unfairly dealt with after being up front and honest about it, that I took the weekend to think about it and then quit the following Monday without notice.
Deb1: Honestly not sure...possibly people's perceptions of others based on limited visual input?
Deb2: Perhaps it was trying to color your view to make you start off negatively before you saw the eyes, to see if it altered how you reacted to them.  Since being in a position of "someone having power over you" is typically negative.

Essay: I was a nurse for a young man who had overdosed on heroin and who now wanted to leave the ER. Although he was alert, oriented, and no longer under the effects of heroin, I did not think that it was safe for him, and attempted to reason with him that it would be better for him to stay and receive treatment. He continued to refuse. I decided to call security and notify the attending physician. The patient was then seen by a psychiatric counselor and involuntarily admitted for further evaluation. I felt sorry for the guy. Because of a mistake he had made, he was no longer in control of the direction of his life. At the same time, however, I felt a little relief that he was being forced to get help. Maybe it would do some good, maybe it wouldn't.
Deb1: Correlation between socioeconomic status and trust of others.
Deb2: I didn't really perceive any correlation.

Essay: I felt very bad. It was my worst feeling​ of my life
Deb1: no
Deb2: no

Essay: I was an assistant manager at Domino's Pizza in Phoenix, AZ.  I answered a phone call from a customer who said their order was incorrect - the wrong pizza was put in the wrong box. When I looked up the order in the computer it showed the driver who had taken the delivery had said the room number was wrong (it was to a nearby motel) and had listed it as a return.  In short, the driver had delivered the food and pocketed the money; she had been thieving.  The driver was a lady named Linda.  She had been our lead driver for over 5 years.  As soon as she was back in the store from the delivery she was on when I had received the call I confronted her.  I hate confrontation.  I felt embarrassed for her.  She was about to get fired, everyone she worked with would eventually find out what happened.  A few of her co workers were good friends of hers.  I happened to be the one who stumbled upon her thievery.  Being part of management,  I would be praised for catching a thief but all I could feel was ashamed and embarrassed FOR her.  Too much empathy, I suppose.  I knew she was in a financially bad spot.  I didn't know if she was thieving on a daily basis or maybe just this once, but I hated having to tell her about the call and that my boss was on his way to terminate her.
Deb1: how giving and trusting a person is willing to be when it is uncertain anyone else will do the same in return
Deb2: Probably.  It made me think about how trust is a hard thing to define.  It depends on the situation. There are some people I would trust with my life but not my personal belongings.  And that would depend on their situation at the time as well.  I've heard that your true character is defined as who you are when we think no one is looking, but I think desperation and poverty has too much weight in those situations.  If I was starving, wouldn't I be more willing to steal money for food?  Wouldn't my ability to be generous change then also?
Deb3: it would be interesting to see the results :)

Essay: I had a former coworker ask for some money. She was going through a very difficult. She was a ​young woman in her early 20s. She had a bad relationship with her parents due to undiagnosed mental illness. She wasn't working at the time and moving from place to place. When she came to me I wasn't in great financial shape. I was living paycheck to paycheck and it was the day before payday. I was down to my last $20. I took her to the store and bought some things. It made me uncomfortable that I was not in the position to just give her the $20. She really needed help but I had to take care of myself.
Deb1: How people react to different people based on gender, race, and religion.
Deb2: I was in a energized positive mood. It made me more open and trusting.

Essay: In my situation, someone had power over me when I was trying to advance in my career. An opportunity was given to me to transfer to a department that was considered a higher position within the company. Unfortunately, my boss denied the request because there was no replacement in my current department. I felt devastated and used, because the position would get me ahead in life, as well as build up my personal knowledge. Months later, I still wonder what I would have became in the new department.
Deb1: The purpose of the study was to put yourself in the moment of an event in your life, and from there, look at the body / facial clues on the other. The idea is to see if you can feel how they feel. Also, apparently my study partner stole my raffle tickets because I haven't heard back from them, after I gave away 100% of them.
Deb2: I don't think so. I feel like the essay was to recollect how I felt that day, and to see if I can recreate the emotions, and to remember how the others work. In the question, it told me to "focus" on the person's eyes.
Deb3: Where's my raffle tickets?! In the survey, it said that my raffle tickets were given to someone and they would get back to me in the end...

Essay: The situation in which I had power was a day where I trained a new employee at my old job. The kid was 18 years old and it was his first job. It was a slow day so the managers told me to show him around and evaluate his preformance, so we could determine what job was best for him. I showed him around and introduced him to everyone. The kid had blue eyes and jet black hair. He was skinny and tall, and kind of shy. He didn't do well as a line cook because he was under too much pressure. So I had him try prep work, in the back. He was much better at prep work, where he could set his own pace and not have others waiting on him. At the end of the day I had to go back to my  boss and tell them my report. In my verbal report I told my boss the events that unfolded and that Iaprove of this worker. In the end I was basically doing the work of the manager and it felt good. I had power but didnt abuse it. I even helped him get/keep the job by vouching for him at the end of the day.
Deb1: I don't know. It could be about how much certain group's trust another group.
Deb2: I think so, If i wrote a smaller, less worded and less thought up answer I would have a shorter survey.

Essay: I had power over deciding the fate of my roommate's relationship with me. I knew that she was more sensitive than me so she would be able to change her mind more easily and it would affect her more
Deb1: power and status
Deb2: no

Essay: I recently applied for a loan over the phone to get my car fixed? I gave the lady all information over the phone. She inserted my information at her computer as we were speaking, after a few minutes, she informed me with those fatal words, "unfortunately at this time, we were not able to get you approved for this loan at this time.
Deb1: This study was about my perception of people by looking at their eyes.
Deb2: Yes it did, it made me visualize.

Essay: The first time I was pulled over by a police officer. I was sitting at a light with my friend and noticed the officer in front of me didn't have his seat on. After the light changed, the police turned left and we went straight. Next thing I know the officer was right behind me and pulling me over. I had no idea what I had done wrong, He got out, took my license and registration and insurance card and then started screaming at me. He claimed I was making fun of him at the light - I can still see his nostrils flaring and spitting coming out of his mouth he was so upset. When I told him I was merely telling my friend that the officer wasn't wearing a seat belt the officer quickly snapped back "I don't have to!" I was scared and powerless in the situation - I thought for sure he was going to take me to jail. After he checked all my paperwork, he stormed back to the car and told me get out of there.
Deb1: To see how you relate to other people
Deb2: No, but I'm still annoyed when I think about the incident sometimes.

Essay: Normally when my husband and I do anything romantic, he usually takes the lead. When I get up enough courage, I will. I'm normally the submissive one in the relationship which is not really a bad thing. I remember one night last year, I made him a candlelight dinner. It was roast, mashed potatoes and gravy, baked macaroni and cheese, kale and lemon meringue pie with raspberry lemonade for drinks. I told him to go in his bedroom and wait for a little while as I set everything up. He had no inkling or idea what was happening. I had trouble getting the candles set up and it made me a little frustrated but I was determined to do this for him since he did so much for me. When I was done setting up, I told him to wash up. I was glad to see him smiling while looking at the table. He says "Wooooowww." He totally didn't expect it. He hugged me and kissed me. We sat down, blessed the food and ate. He told me no woman has ever done this for him before. I gave him a slice of pie and put whipped cream on it as I did for myself. After we were done, I sat on his lap and kissed him. He acted so appreciative. I was really happy he enjoyed it.
Deb1: I think this survey was about how people perceive others in positions of control and how they feel if they are superior to others.
Deb2: I don't think the answers I wrote affected any questions in the survey.
Deb3: I really enjoyed this survey. It was pretty interesting.

Essay: The time that comes back to mind is when I was in bootcamp. The drill instructors had complete control over our movements, when we ate, when we cleaned, and when we slept. They had a mission to break us down and build us back up. Plenty times I wanted it to end, but kept pushing myself to go farther and farther. You could tell when the tearing down ended and the building up began because it was like night and day how they treated you.
Deb1: how people are perceived
Deb2: no

Essay: My boss has the power over me through her evaluation of my work.  My evaluation impacts my ability to move within the company. She took the situation very lightly--rushing through a lot of the details.  She also seemed taken back (her posture changed and she physically moved back a little bit) when I asked intelligent questions like "Does this have a monetary impact?"  She has short peppery, gray hair that is cut in a non-stylish way and has a boxy walk that really gets under my skin.
Deb1: Judging peoples perceptions
Deb2: I think it impacted my mood.

Essay: When I was in my twenties I left my husband. My parents decided to sue me for custody of my children. I had to go to court and fight for my children against my own parents. My mother had always tried to control my life and hold her power over me. This upset me greatly and caused great sadness.
Deb1: How are feelings affect others.
Deb2: I don't think it affected my answers.

Essay: I'm a teaching assistant at my college, as of last semester. The first day I ran my own lab I was incredibly nervous to begin with, but I had one particular student, Tom, who was twice my age, knowledgeable about chemistry, and seemingly argumentative. I felt a bit intimidated, but kept my confident mask on, got through the day, and continued to improve. Now I look forward to teaching!
Deb1: To gain an understanding of how political affiliations could affect someone's' view of themselves, their place in society, and how they view the society itself.
Deb2: No I don't thing that it affected my answers much.

Essay: At my last job, my supervisor was a very controlling individual. Some would call him anal retentive. He always had to know what was going on and have a hand in everything. He was also apt to take credit for things his employees had done or to "throw employees under the bus" when it suited him. I had recently finished my master's degree and I wanted to ask the CEO for a raise. I also wanted to sit down and talk with the CEO about possible advancement in my career at the company. I knew that I needed to clear this with my immediate supervisor so that he was aware of what I wanted to do. So, I informed my supervisor. But instead of allowing me to go have the conversation with the CEO myself, the supervisor wanted to go talk to him by himself. I didn't think that was fair, because I didn't trust him to make the best case for me. But I had no choice. The talk was put off for several weeks, and the end result was less than I had hoped for. I was very disappointed.
Deb1: How willing I am to trust a random stranger with my chances of increasing my wealth or success. How trusting I am of people in general.
Deb2: The essay I wrote most likely negatively affected my answers to the question in the survey because it made me think about a time when I had to put my trust in someone and was let down with the results.

Essay: We held elections in a small organization I am a part of. I felt that the candidates for the organization's presidency were treating me very differently than they do normally on various occasions, because I had power to influence the outcome of the elections and give or withhold something that each candidate wanted badly. I felt as though their interactions with me were not genuinely motivated by friendship but by a desire to influence me to support their campaigns.
Deb1: My best guess is that the survey correlates how having power over others influences the perception of emotional cues in others, energizes or exhausts, and affects altruism or selfishness in a decision making exercise.
Deb2: It may have made me less trusting as I recalled sensing ulterior, self-serving intentions in others.
Deb3: I would be interested to learn the purpose and findings of the study.

Essay: it was my boss who owned the company for which I worked. We worked in the same office and I felt that she was very controlling over every aspect of my work. She made me feel as if I did not have free will.

Essay: I can think of several work related instances when supervisors had power over me, however the instance that is standing out to me was in my personal life with my parents.  As I entered into adulthood in my early 20s, my parents had less and less power over me.  Once particular instance though when they still had power over me was financially after I moved to Thailand.  Because I needed help funding my trip, they paid for my plane ticket both there and back, which created a sort of power over me.  After spending six months teaching, I wanted to stay longer and extend my contract.  Because they had purchased my plane ticket, and I could still not afford to reimburse them, they had the power to veto my decision.  They felt it was time for me to move home and get a "real job."  This was a very frustrating, emotionally-charged situation.  I remember feeling upset and angry, but helpless to change the situation.
Deb1: Perhaps the study is to look at how people form perceptions when they feel that they are not in a place of power. Or more generally, how power relates to perceptions?

Essay: I was being evaluated by a psychiatrist who had the power to commit me to a mental holding facility indefinitely.  I felt trapped by the psychiatrist, he had complete power over my life.  I also felt he was of below average intelligence, which infuriated me.  This man could decide my fate simply because he bowed to the higher education system and crossed his t's and dotted his i's, meanwhile, in reality, he was a dunce.  Anyone of intelligence who cared to, could become as proficient as this man in psychiatry in about three days reading in a library.  Yet, this imbecile could banish me to the hellish existence inside a mental hospital, which would very likely drive me ACTUALLY insane.  I had to lie and try to determine what this person needed to hear to give me back my autonomy.  I couldn't possibly hope to reason with him.  It was absolutely enraging and frustrating and hopeless.  Imagine being stuck in a room with an unpredictable child who has a button that, if pressed, can blow you up.   You can't reason with the child.  You can only hope to guess how he will react to what you say.
Deb1: To find out how a visualization exercise affected peoples feelings and perceptions
Deb2: It didn't affect my answers, but it did affect my mood.  However, I have been in the habit of answering questions with rationality, not emotion.

Essay: This was a job interview over the phone.  There was no face to face contact but given the geographical distance a phone interview was more feasible.  I was nervous about the interview and prepared some sample questions and answers prior to my scheduled time to be called.  But I would say that I was less nervous than I would have been with a typical face to face interview.  I was scheduled to be called by an interviewer at 5pm, and waited in a silent room in my home waiting to take the phone call.  I was nervous because I really wanted this job in particular.  As soon as I called, I greeted the interviewer, told her about myself, and as she asked further questions, the interview seemed to become more casual and less formal.  Despite this, I made an effort to continue to impress her, and towards the ending the interviewer said that I was hired and that she would start to send me some paperwork.  I was completely elated, and did not expect a hiring decision so soon.

Essay: It felt like an adrenaline rush. I remember my younger sibling and how irritating and grating they were getting with every single word they speak. They just kept taunting about how terrible I am, how I had no friends, and how they blamed me for the reason why my grandpa died. Later, they claimed that they knew that they were doing it on purpose to get a rise out of me, but I could never forget how terrified they look the moment I finally screamed "SHUT UP". How wide their eyes became as they slowly backed away. I remember blacking out, so I don't remember any specific details other than that the room turned into a mess. According to my mom, she said that I picked up and threw several things across the room including a mattress and several textbooks. I immediately began apologizing and regret how my temper got out of control. My sibling brushed it off and said it was not a big deal, and to stop being so sensitive, but agreed to not bring it up again. It wasn't until later around high school when my relationship with them improved, but even though I snapped, I was a bit happy that for one moment I was able to let my feelings out.

Every eye varies from person to person, and shows the individual's traits in personality and character. It's similar for the part where we imagine "power over someone". There's a variety of emotions going on when one has power over someone else - relief, anger, fear, etc., and depending on their personality, background, and beliefs it varies a lot.
Deb2: I think so, because depending on my mood, memories, morals and beliefs, background, and environment around me, it can affect how I answer specific questions.

Essay: I was in the Navy, deployed in Japan, in a anti- sub hunter group. We had been there for six months and due to go back to our home station at Moffett Field, Ca. There was a snag of some type with our relieving squadron so it was determined that some of us had to stay back for several weeks to assist in the getting the replacements up to speed with the base's facilities, or lack thereof. Along with myself one of the people chosen to stay behind was a young tech. He had an unpronounceable Polish name so we just called him 'Splash', He was devastated by being on what he called 'the losers list' and told everyone he thought it was wrong that he was chosen. I sat him down and pointed out to him that it was actually a recognition of his abilities as a tech and also reminded him that I had been sent as an advance party of one and had actually been in Japan two weeks longer than anyone else. I also realized that if I were left behind to be in charge I didn't really want him with me. His attitude would just make it harder on everyone so I told him that I would speak with the Maintenance Officer and see if I couldn't get him sent home with the Squadron. I asked him to calm down and not go crying to anyone, that I would take care of it. I was highly respected by all so I was sure I would be listened to. Unfortunately 'Splash' couldn't refrain from making himself a pest so by the time I went in to the shop the next morning it had already been decided that he would stay just as punishment for being such a pain. I sympathized with him but in the end if he had listened the outcome would have been different.
Deb1: Well you certainly were not interested in the ramblings of an old man so it must be how perceptive one will be after recalling a period of power, if you can perceive the feeling of others and how you would respond to those of different cultures.

Essay: About ten years ago as a young man, I took a job as a salesman for a home remodel company.  I had no sales experience and had struck out for the first month on the job. Would this be the one?  Would this person be the first to say "yes".  I was nervous and excited, I needed the sale to boost my income and to prove my worth to the company.  I remember sitting in the open living room of the A frame style home and finishing my sales pitch with "....And all I need to get started is a 50% deposit, and I'll place your order...."  The husband and wife, each in their fifties or so, took very little time deciding.  They were kind looking people.  Maybe they felt bad for the kid, obviously new to his trade, trying to support his family.  Maybe they just really liked what I was selling.  Regardless, husband and wife each had a small grin and a kindhearted look in their eyes, as she politely said "OK" and he reached for the check book.

Essay: I was a server at the time at a Greek restaurant.  During the day, I had accidentally hit the side of the coffee pot on the corner of the coffee machine, resulting in the coffee pot basically exploding.  The pot was full, of course, and I burned myself and the arm of one of my coworkers.  The manager, the owner's son, was not at all happy with me.  They had a strict rule that no managers were allowed to be alone with any employee when speaking to them in their office.  However, he grabbed my arm and brought me into his office and closed the door.  He would not let me out, and refused to let anyone else inside.  He told me that he could fire me at any moment and that I should be grateful that he is trying to work this out with me.  He told me that I would have to go on a date with him if I wanted to keep my job.  I told him I was engaged and he said he didn't care.  He was my manager and therefore I needed to listen to him to be able to keep my employment.  I decided to agree and do what he told me I needed to do.  The following week, after the date, he brought me into his office alone again.  He proceeded to tell me that I would need to kiss him to keep my job.  I felt as though he was trying to brainwash me.  I refused and he fired me.  I then called his father and told him that if he did not do something about his son I would report it.  He offered me my job back but refused to fire his son, so I did not take the job.

Essay: I participated in a volunteer program to train for a job. The program required so many class hours and 160 clinical hours to be completed by a certain date. As a program participant, I was not paid, but I had to show up and work a for 8 to 9 hours as an employee. The supervisor over the clinic was not a people person. They had poor social skills and no ethics training. This person was the point of contact for assignment duties. One day upon arrival the person I was to shadow was working at an out of town clinic. I had no prior knowledge of the trip. So I went to the supervisor and informed them of the situation. The supervisor told me the the person was at an out of town clinic and asked me why I didn't go. I again informed the supervisor that I had no knowledge that I was supposed to go out of town and asked to be assigned to someone else for the day. The supervisor's attitude took a turn for the worse. They flicked their hand (in a shooing motion) and informed me that they had no one else for me to shadow, that I should have found out the schedule for the week, and then instructed me to go to sit or walk around. At the beginning of clinic we were instructed to not look idle or congregate. I felt let down. I came to the supervisor for guidance, and they provided me with none. Instead of saying, I don't have an assignment for you right now, give me ten minutes and I'll find you something to do, they told me to do nothing. So I ended up sitting behind the counter studying for a test. I went took the test, passed it, and then asked a worker if I could shadow them for the day. The worker happily agreed. Later the supervisor passed me in the hall and I learned so much from that worker. I learned from that experience sometimes you have to take matter in your own hands to get the most out of an opportunity.
Deb1: I think this study was to test how people who've been in powerless situations utilize power. We were first asked to imagine a situation where we had no power. Then asked to write about it. Then shown pictures to judge, and later asked about raffle tickets. We had power to judge and power over the raffle tickets.
Deb2: Yes, from my essay, I wrote what I learned having gone through the experience. I live by the motto treat others as you want to be treated. So when it came to the raffle ticket decision I gave as I wanted to receive.
Deb3: No this was a fun survey. I hope you find what you're looking for.

Essay: My situation is a time when I was working and I was a lead/shift supervisor of a place where I worked. I had the power over everyone as to what their they were to do and so on. One day a told this young man whom had worked for a little while on the veggie machine. He had worked this job several times he knew the safety rules to follow. I also went over them again before he started working. Within a hour or so he started screaming because he cut his finger very badly. However, he was not using the guard as he was told to do. The first thing I had to do was get gloves on and wrap his finger. I then had to tell my cleaner (the person that kept the work area clean at all times) to get all safety gear on and start cleaning and sanitizing the area. I then immediately took my worker to the nurse. I can still remember this guy whom towered over me because I am so short and he was so tall. Plus, he looked like he could have been a football player. He had such a worried scared look on his face like a little kid waking from a nightmare. I immediately knew why. Not only did his finger hurt very badly but I knew and asked are you clean. His answer was no I am not I will fail the drug test is there is anyway I don't have to take it. As a supervisor I told him yes you have to take one and you will have to live with the what happens. I will always remember the look on his face and having to tell him yes accidents happen and you get hurt but you know that at any given time you can be tested for drugs for getting hurt. I felt like I was having a talk with my own kid.
Deb1: I feel it was to determine how we see a situation we are in with people. How understanding, trusting and so on.
Deb2: Yes, I simply answered my questions to the way I feel about things personally.

Essay: I was in a group interview to become a resident assistant at my college. The ones making the selection were current RA's, many of which were my peers. They all held clipboards, and each one was in charge of evaluating one of us as we did ridiculous tasks that were similar to group activities designed to bring people and teams together, though we were competing against one another. Essay: I was an employee at a County Government office, I was working on a project that had failed for the managers in the past.  The County Manager told our department managers some heads were going to roll if they didn't get the new permit system running.  I was hired as a front office clerk but I had a back ground in computers so I had offered my services.  The Middle Manager head of my department allowed me to work on the project.  The co-workers were not on board with the new system and didn't want the change which made the transition difficult, probably part of the reason why it had failed previously.  I was given a $1.00 hour bonus but because the other staff resented my time away from the front office I needed to change positions to the back office with new duties.  During the transition it was a slight raise in pay so the Middle Manager cut my project bonus down.  I made the new system go live in November of that year and that is when my agreement to help ended but the real problems with the Middle Manager begin. /  / The Middle Manager requested me to continue helping the transition so I requested a raise and he said I was blackmailing him.  Then I was nominated for an award because of going above and beyond, I received the invitation by email but was told by the Middle Manager the day before the ceremony not to attend because the other staff members might complain so they took the award away, they said for another date but I knew I wouldn't be around long enough.  The staff continued to complain wanting training not how to use the system but how to program SQL.  I did not have the qualifications to teach the class by I directed the staff to learn through the program I learned on within a week the Middle Manager removed all my permissions to access the new program (which I still needed to use in my current position.)  so I couldn't do my job.  I resigned the next morning. /  / The Middle Manager had complete control over my job, my raises, my permissions to work, and awards given to me by the other Managers.  I had no other option but to walk away.  I felt hopeless and powerless to control my own destiny through hard work, I felt a little unappreciated but mostly I felt let down by my own skills.
Deb1: The study is to see how people see themselves and other people after taking a few moments to feel an unpleasant experience.  Do their perceptions change of others after that bad experience.
Deb2: I am not sure, I tend to stay away from others more, I am not comfortable with authority figures much maybe that is why I am now out of work.
