Essay: A few weeks ago, I sold my car to my sister. Although she was excited to be getting a car because it would enable her to get to her current job and allow her to take an internship during the summer, it was clear to me she was a bit upset about the situations. She's always felt I've gotten more than she has from our parents, and this was just another example of that: although I bought the car from my parents initially, now it was even more used than when I purchased it. / I can remember the conversation we had about the car. In the past year, I'd sunk more than $2000 into repairs the mechanic told me I could've put off. But I knew the car was going to my sister, so I bit the bullet and payed for everything: brand new tires, an entire ball joint and steering arm replacement, the clock springs in the steering column, the struts, and a recharge of the AC system. / I knew I was in a position of power because I could ask her to pay whatever I wanted, and as long as it was less than $6000, she'd be getting a deal she couldn't find anywhere else. But instead, I asked her for $3000. It was probably more than she could afford, and I wanted to do right by her. But even still, she had a look of betrayal in her eyes, as though she was upset that I was even asking her to pay at all.
Deb1: I'm not entirely sure, but I'd guess it has something to do about how our experiences of power are associated with how we responded to the ticket question.
Deb2: I don't necessarily know that it did. Maybe thinking about my sister made me feel magnanimous, but I'll tell you what, I think I would have done that either way. If I give The Other 1000 tickets, they've got 3000. If they even given me 1001, that's 1 more ticket than I would've had before, and they walk away with 1999 tickets. And if they don't give me any tickets, I don't feel too bad either. Because if this is a real drawing and EVERY person is getting at least 1000 tickets (multiplied up to 3000 for the other), my chances of winning are pretty darn slim. So I figure I didn't lose much either way.

Society thinks if you are rich you are everything and treat you like that too. Some rich people are so rude and hurtful and wasteful. I'm sure they are lonely too with no real friends.

Essay: In this particular situation I was the assistant coach of a youth basketball team, but it was maddening because the head coach knew nothing of the sport and yet had the final say in all decisions. She would always have one of those stupid smirks on her face when she got to make a decision that I had no say in. I felt like I was trapped and on edge all the time because the kids deserved a much better experience than that.

Deb2: No I don't think the essay I wrote affected my answers in the study, though it did force me to think and really focus on what I was doing. /

Essay: The cops held me in handcuffs behind my back. Someone had jumped out of the back of my car to the move the barricade on the street so I could drive through the alley way. The music was loud and the people in my car were equally loud, making it hard for me to hear that the police had come knocking on the car. The only problem was that we had all been drinking, me included. To make matters worse, I wasn't 21. The car had gunned in neutral, I was still relatively new with driving a manual car. The cops had thought I wasn't going to stop but that was not the case at all. After a couple of respectful answers to the cops when I was handcuffed I was allowed to leave. It was the closest call I've ever had before in my life and I've never driven with any amount of alcohol in my body ever again. To this day I still wonder why they let me off the hook in a car that I borrowed from my friend and when they probably knew we had all been drinking.

Essay: I was the lady's manager in a retail store in Colorado. She had missed work a lot because of a skin disease. My manager at the home office required that I fired her because she hadn't been with the company long enough to take leave. I had only been her manager for a few months and had only ever seen her maybe 3 times in my time in the position. I had to sit her down and break the news to her. She begged and pleaded to keep her job, but there was nothing I could do. She cried a lot. I just wanted to hold her and even offered my shoulder for her to cry on. She blamed me though. She said it was because I was new to the store and wanted to make an name for myself to not put up with anyone's crap. She eventually stopped crying and stood up and called me some names before leaving my office and slamming the door behind her.  /  / I felt horrible. I didn't know what to do. I felt torn between being a caring human being and being a manager paid to do a job - a job that at the end of the day affects other people and their wellbeing.
Deb1: Possibly how we treat other people over ourselves or how good we are at "reading" each other. I'm not really sure. It could be a variety of different things.

Essay: I was the chair of my honors program's recruitment committee during my junior and senior undergraduate years, and I, along with other members of my committee, had a lot of power over which applicants were admitted to our program and which applicants were not. However, I remember thinking that she would do well if given the chance because she seemed to have the right attitude.  I pushed for her acceptance and she later became a member of the program.  I remember feeling like I was doing what was right for the program, which made me feel good, and I remember seeing her later doing well in the program, which made me feel somewhat wise in that I picked out her potential where other people missed it.

Essay: The situation was recent - it was my boss at my last place of employment. I had been employed with this company for nearly ten years and had gained a lot of respect from those I extended my service to.  However, because she was in a position of "power," she held more sway over HR and the executive management team, and as such maneuvered me into a situation where I would be stuck to continue answering to the unfair standards she had placed upon me, while a peer of mine was treated with the utmost respect by her (while not having that same respect among the rest of the company - an opposite situation as myself).  This upset me greatly because it disrupted my philosophy that if you work hard, you'll reap the benefits of your hard work.  The real result was that despite my hard work, I was unjustly forced out of my job - noticed not only me but others within the company who also felt powerless to do anything.

This is bound to make me leery of people and think a bit negatively about people's intentions. If I were happier or in a better place, my attitudes may be a bit different.

Essay: A situation that stands out most to me was a time where I convinced the coach of my Academic Decathlon team to make me a co-captain of the team. My reason for doing this primarily was to fuel my own ego, gain more power, and prove my competence to one of my peers who I believed thought my judgments were less than sound. Nevertheless, I made a highly convincing argument and without this one peer's prior knowledge, became co-captain of the team. The basis for my "argument" regarding my ascent to being co-captain, was that I was able to assemble a small study group comprises of the students who's scores were low, and sit down with them to pinpoint what they did not understand and go over material with them in a more careful and copacetic manner. Once this group was officially made, I remember how intently everyone listened to me, as if I had so much knowledge to bequeath that they needed to hang on every words I said to absorb some of it. In truth, I was lazy; I scored well on my tests but never studied, and put in very little effort that year since it was my last year in high-school and because well, I am lazy in general. But that feeling of hierarchical dominance, and the sense of "you guys are looking up to me because it SEEMS as though I am smarter than you" was more than addicting. It wasn't something new to me, I was lazy throughout high-school but I suppose because of the way my mind worked, I was seen as smarter than most and often tutored other students or took the brunt of the work during group projects and such. The manifestation of my ego during these instances were so addictive, and gave me this shallow, fragile sense of worth and arrogance that was just enough to make me feel like I had more worth as a human being than most. These instances of "power" (if you can really define it as power) laid the ground-work for a delicate ego, and a split personality that seemed genuine and humble to those I would speak with, but in reality, was plagued with arrogance, elitism, and an incomparable sense of pride.
Deb1: I am guessing that the purpose of this study is to compare the feelings of people who have been in power, versus their empathy and ability to relate to other people's emotions.
Deb2: I do not believe my anecdote about a position of power I was in affected my answers in the survey.
Deb3: This is a very interesting study; it made me think a lot about my own desires and flaws which I do not dwell on usually. I would love to see what the results of this study are.

Essay: In college, I worked as a shift supervisor at a popular restaurant. Some of the employees I managed were my age, but some of them were much older than I was. One of the older employees was named Robin. She has red hair, that she always wore in a ponytail. She had bangs, and most of the time, pieces of her hair would fall in her face. Her appearance was always a bit in disarray without actually being what I would consider sloppy. I do not recall a very specific conversation I had with Robin, but I can recall a general sense of the encounters. I felt really out of place giving orders to Robin--well, really to any employee older than me. It was uncomfortable, and I still felt like just a regular coworker, despite my promotion. She would listen intently as I spoke, making steady eye contact--usually smiling, sometimes with her eyes. She always had something funny or clever to say. I liked that about her. She would go off in her usual frantic way, rushing off to tend to tables. I did not really feel like I was speaking from a place of power. I enjoyed the idea of having the capability of giving instruction to others, but in reality, it was never really something I found a lot of pride in.
Deb1: This study may have something to do with social relations--how individuals interact with other people and how certain personal qualities impact those interactions and how they are valued/perceived.

Essay: I wouldn't say that this situation is an incident -- that usually implies a negative circumstance. People have power over others in many different normal circumstances. For myself, I distinctly remember the few job interviews I've had as that is the most discernible and accepted periods in which someone has complete authority over your future. Especially when there are two people in the room, evaluating everything that you say, every small quirk in your bodily movements. They, with blue and brown eyes, are looking at you and through you, up and down, side to side. In times of disappointment or surprise there may be that small feeling of self-resentment coming from yourself as they take a note in their clipboard, most likely marking a mistake that you made or how you are coming off as an inferior candidate, someone that less deserves that particular salary or hourly earnings. All I can feel is pressure to not mess up as I can see in their face that they have done these interviews enough that screening for my mistakes is easy, and the next ranking candidate can take over any time they want.
Deb1: General trust of others and underlying currents of exerting power over those you may not trust.
Deb2: Yeah, it inspired more negative feelings inside myself for the rest of the answers.

Essay: I immediately thought of my abusive ex-boyfriend, and the time he broke my nose. We were fighting (as usual), and I thought that I would finally stand up for myself. I stood up as he was still sitting on the bed, and started to yell at him. He then stood up and got directly into my face and started screaming at me. I pushed him back to get him away from me, and he said, "Oh you want to fight like the man in the relationship?" and got up and put me in a headlock. And he said that he would show me what happens when I try to act like the man. He then uppercut my nose with all of his force and blood went everywhere. The bed, the floor, my dresser, the wall. Everywhere. I started screaming and I just started running. It was the middle of winter, I had no shoes or jacket on, but I knew I just needed to run. I made it to the community laundry room, blood soaked, and I locked myself inside the bathroom they had in it. I was so terrified that he was looking for me, so I told myself I had to quit crying or he would hear me and find me. I started grabbing paper towels and just watched the blood pour out onto them. A thought crossed through my head that the blood would never stop coming, and I would eventually die. All of a sudden, I heard a couple of people come into the laundry room, and I froze. I didn't want anyone to see me in that situation. I felt like nothing. Like a maggot. And I had never felt so powerless, stuck in that bathroom. He was in my home, a home that I pay for, and I'm the one who asked him to live with me. I put myself in that situation, and yet with all of those choices that I had made, I had no control. I sat on that cold bathroom floor for around an hour until it was so cold that I couldn't feel my feet anymore. So I made the walk back home. We had a very small apartment, so as soon as you open the door you see directly into the bedroom. As I entered the apartment, I saw him sitting up in bed, glaring at me. I still had tears running down my face, but it was silent. He just stared as I came into the room, and he said NOTHING. Not a single sound. Not an apology, or anything. Normally when he would hurt me, he would apologize profusely, which would be why I stayed with him ,because I really thought he was sorry. But in this moment, I saw the person he truly was. A twisted, demented soul, and I had never been more scared in my life. Who was this monster I was sharing my life with? How can he appear so normal to everyone else, but really be this person inside? And yet, I stayed with him still. He had me believing that nobody else on the planet would want me. And so I stayed. I stayed for about a month more. Then I woke up one morning, and it hit me like a wave. I knew I had to get out of there. And with that realization, I left.
Deb1: I'm honestly not sure. If I had to guess, I would think that it is about how you perceive yourself and others in different situations.
Deb2: Yes. The essay I wrote is about something that is very personal to me. It affected my mood for the remainder of the survey, and left me feeling very somber. I then did not feel very optimistic.
Deb3: I appreciate being able to write that survey. I have never written about that experience, and I've never even spoke to someone about it in that much detail for fear of being ridiculed. So, in a way, this was a form of therapy for me, so thank you.

Essay: My boss was giving me my annual performance review to determine how much of a raise I would get. We were sitting in his very Spartan office, which was fairly chilly despite it being September in New Orleans. He said that I would not be receiving a raise, due to poor performance. This angered me, as he had done nothing but praise my work since I was hired. I told him that I felt it unfair to penalize me for problems with my work without having given me any chance to correct the mistakes. When I asked for specific examples, he grew visibly nervous and told me that it was actually because of a vacation I had taken the month prior. Again, I was angry, because he had personally approved my vacation. He wouldn't hear any more discussion, making me feel like he saw me as disposable, but his eagerness to get me out of his office caused me to become suspicious. Even as he was seeing me out, he refused to meet my eye. His appearance was less put together than usual, and he had been acting more stressed lately, so I began to believe that the real issue was that he didn't have the money to give me a raise. I left the meeting feeling both angry and sad, for I believe I would have been fine, or at least less angry, if he had simply told me as such. Instead, he lied to me and tried to blame me, diminishing my trust of him. Ultimately, I had no ability to change his mind, regardless of the reality.
Deb1: How authority affects trust. Not sure, the Prisoner's Dilemma is throwing me.
Deb2: I think recalling an unpleasant experience made me a bit more prone to not wanting to be active.

Essay: I went camping with some friend in the Adirondacks during my late high school years.  We were unknowingly trespassing on private land and were arrested by a state trooper who saw our smoke and came up the mountain to our camp.  We thought he would just tell us to leave but he took us in and told us we had to appear before a judge.  We were taken to a courthouse and the judge came to town just for the occasion.  We were asked a lot of questions by the trooper then the judge came in, put on his robes, and went over the case.  In the end we were given suspended sentences and allowed to go home. /  / But until we found out the verdict we had no idea what might happen.  And that situation was very uncomfortable and not a little frightening, as none of us had ever been arrested before, much less in front of a judge.  I think this discomfort was exacerbated by the fact that this was completely unexpected and we had broken this law entirely unknowingly and had not caused any damage or loss to anyone....and it was a sickening feeling to sit there and think that this innocent mistake on our part might possibly have some serious consequences, depending on the whims of this country judge (whose name, I still remember, was Roy).  Part of me wanted to protest, but another part of still sensed that cooperation with this process, even if I thought that process unwarranted, was probably the best way to get out unscathed.  So I was cooperative, maybe even obsequious.  But in the end we were allowed to go on our way.  /  / Looking back now I think this was all pretty much a show intended to give us a scare so we wouldn't do something like that again.   And I still think that was unwarranted,  I think a mere warning from the trooper would have been more than enough.
Deb1: Not sure.  At first it seemed to be exploring how people feel in situations where another seems to have power over them, or even exploring what those situations are.  But the following material, such as associating the eyes with an adjective, does not seem congruent with that.  So I'm stumped.
Deb2: No, I do not - if there was such an effect I was not conscious of it.
Deb3: I think the question about how you trust different groups was difficult because in every one of those groups the answer depends on the individual, not the group that individual is in.  Yet the answer structure forces me to lump everybody in that group into one trust level,  and that is absolutely not the way I experience it.

Essay: The situation would be with my six year old son.  He is undiagnosed with either high functioning autism or some other sort of social disorder which makes it very hard for him to communicate. I felt mostly angry but I always also feel at the same time really terrible.  I hate having to do this to him but I realize it is for his own good to at least try new foods.  He tends to get so angry that he shouts and starts to shake really bad.  At that point I sent him to time out and then walked over there with him.  I rubbed his back and gently asked him to calm down while he cried in my lap.  When he sufficiently calmed down I explained to him that it was his choice and that he could either eat and get a dessert or he could choose not to eat the food, I would make him a sandwich, and he would not get the dessert.  He eventually tried the food however, although I cannot remember if he liked it or not.  However, I do remember, mostly because this works 90-95% of the time for me how calming it is for him to go into time out and just cry on me.  I also know that usually by me giving him the choice and explaining it to him that way he usually ends up trying the food, even if it is only one bite.  So in the end I believe I felt relief.
Deb1: I do not know in the slightest.  Something about how certain types of people handle power?
Deb2: I do not believe so.  I have the kind of personality I can usually look at things from a fairly detached perspective.
Deb3: Shorter than I expected.  I hope my experiences help.

After a few weeks I had decided that the employee needed to be terminated and that she needed to do it. This was her first time firing someone. I told her that if she wanted to been seen as a figure of authority and be respected as such that she had to discipline people and this was going to be the start. I could tell the she didn't feel comfortable with doing it and was empathetic to the situation as I remembered the first time that I had to do the same. I vividly remembered the feeling of wanting to avoid confrontation. I could almost feel her elevation in anxiety. But, after giving her instructions on how to professionally confront someone and to do it without coming across as combative, I instructed her to go ahead with it. These types of situations usually have a wide range of outcomes. From best case senario, the employee understands their wrong doing and accepts the discipline, to worst case, they become irate and offensive. She recieved something closer to the latter. I could tell that the situation had caused her to be upset but it also helped to prepare her for future situations like this.
Deb1: Maybe a study of how one's empathy directs how they look at themselves as well as their place in society and other's place as well.
Deb2: I do not. I consider myself to be a very humble and empathetic person. I try to always put myself in the place of another before I judge them or their actions. I also never try to compare where I am in life or my level of success based on the level of success of others. It's all perspective, in my opinon.
Deb3: I enjoy when the studies are thought provoking and do not tell the purpose of the study upfront. Even more when they ask what the survey taker feels the study was about.

Essay: I have recalled one particular situation early last week. An employee wanted to add special supplies onto the staples order I was placing. I need to approve all supplies being requested. I thought about whether or not the items were really needed. I denied their request and did not add the items to my staples order. I felt a little bad for the denial. The other person involved was not happy.
Deb1: My guess is that this survey has to do with power and decision making based on the beginning of the survey and then giving me the option to give away some of my tickets.
Deb2: I do not think it had an effect
Deb3: I am still wondering if "Other" gave me any tickets :)

Essay: I was the lead for my old job and I had power over giving a worker of mine a raise. I felt really confident that the raise would be approved because this worker was a great employee and I had no reason to deny a raise in wages. I felt really confident that they would be happy. We sat down at my desk and it was a male co worker and just right away I looked at him and said ok you have been approved for a wage increase. I said is there anything you want to talk or ask me about. The worker smiled and said nope and then we both just talked about random things not regarding the raise.
Deb1: I think the purpose is to see how we can use our memory to do different things such as recall certain situations and to see if we can read what other are thinking.
Deb2: I honestly don't know if it did or didn't. I think it may have just shown what kind of person I am maybe or what I can recall in great detail. I would probably say it didn't affect my answers if I had to choose.
Deb3: Please feel free to contact me for any future surveys. Thank you.

Essay: I was working at a toy store on Black Friday. A woman came in asking for a specific item that was not on the shelves. She asked me if I could please check in the back to see if there were any left. I obliged and went into the back room to dig through boxes to look for the item. Although I was tired the woman was nice and I felt I should do my best to find what she wanted. I found one item at the bottom of a box and brought it out to her.
Deb1: How socio-economic class affects perception of others of various racial/social classes
Deb2: No.

Essay: I was being evaluated at my old job and was being scored by the safety manager. He was telling me all the stuff I had wrong in the store and I was feeling intimated at that point. I knew he had more power and knowledge than me so I had no choice but to listen to him and take his advice for next times visit.
Deb1: To think of a time when you had no power over something and how you would distribute something with a stranger.
Deb2: No, the rest of the questions were different than the first question. The first was having no power over a situation and the next was having power.

Essay: I was working in customer service when my manager came over to me and began yelling at me for helping a customer too much. I was very angry and began to yell back. I visualized hitting her over and over again, but I knew if she didn't attack first I would get in trouble. I just kept shouting back until someone came in and calmed us both Dow. She tried to write disciplinary action against me, but I had all the employees and I got the name of the customer. When her boss tried to enforce disciplinary action, I called on all my witnesses. They were very upset. It felt very good to get the best of them.
Deb1: The purpose of this study was to determine how sensitive people really are to each other when there is no familiar connection just a gut feeling.
Deb2: No.

Essay: I used to be an assistant manager at a retail store. The manager assigned me with the task of firing a new employee due to a mix up concerning their background check. I did not want to complete this task. Having the power to fire someone, and having to go through with it is not a pleasant experience. Throughout the duration of her employment, I got to know her, and she would tell me about her children, and being a single, working parent and trying to get her life together. I did fire her. She was extremely upset. It took her a long time to get hired, and now she was losing that job, income, and stability. I could see the desperation and emotions on her face. She was crying and explaining about the discrepancy on her background report. That it was a misunderstanding and the charges were dropped. But even though I had the power to fire her, I did not have the power to fix the further backpedaling in her life. I felt miserable. It was as if I could feel her pain with her.
Deb1: The purpose of this study is to compare personality types with empathy.
Deb2: Yes. The writing exercise caused me to re-live the experience. By doing so, I experienced those emotions, which affected my mood. This caused my answers to be affected.
Deb3: I find different personality types interesting to observe. I think that the results of this study will be very compelling.

Essay: The event I am thinking of was when I was interviewing for a Law Enforcement job. There were three high ranking Officers asking me questions. I remember feeling nervous and a bit intimidated. It was tough knowing they could control the outcome of my interview.
Deb1: I think this test was about how people feel about others and hoe they would treat them.
Deb2: I don't think so.

Essay: I was starting to develop new upholstery styles for the upcoming convention when the president of the company came in and told me that if my designs weren't successful I would have to find a new job. I was outraged as he had promoted me to vice-president just 6 months earlier and this was my first attempt at bringing new designs to the company. As it turned out several of my designs are still being sold by the company 17 years later, a testament to my innovative designs.
Deb1: To gauge personality and how it relates to political biases.
Deb2: Yes, maybe it made me remember to be fair when making decisions about other people.

Essay: I was sitting with the person, hugging. The person was larger than I am.  They told me they would not let me get up and go. They were somewhat teasing, but I felt extremely trapped and panicked.
Deb1: To determine how feeling powerless effects your emotions.
Deb2: Yes.  I think it made me angry and took me back to when I felt a little helpless, so the answers I chose could have been from a meeker perspective.

Essay: My dad gave me his credit card to buy Christmas presents for myself and my two sisters. I had the power to determine what gifts they got and how much to spend on each person. I felt good about it because I know my sisters well and I knew that I would be able to pick out gifts that they would enjoy I ended up buying them both almost everything they wanted, so they were both extremely happy.
Deb1: The purpose of this study was to find out how people's personal attitudes and feelings affected their perception of others
Deb2: I'm not sure if it had any effect
Deb3: I thought this study was really interesting!

Essay: I was hired as a retail manager for a local chain of stores a few years ago. I had the pleasure of working with some really great people and a few that were not so great. The person that came to mind during the visualization was a girl about ten years younger than me. I always felt like she was very misunderstood. I loved working with her. Mostly because I felt like she looked to me for guidance, but also because I could tell she was not used to having people be very straight forward with her - and because my candid personality is not widely accepted- we got along great. She was like the little sister I never had. She was inquisitive and irritated me at times, but for the most part she was a great girl with a lot of potential. She did not have much self-confidence from what I could tell, but she seemed to relax and be herself more when I was the one managing the shift. Other managers complained about her work under the supervision of their shift, but I knew it wasn't her but rather the way they managed her and the shift. When the yearly evaluation came around I made sure that the higher-ups took a look at my evaluation and compared it closely to the other managers evaluations and continued accordingly. I had the power to speak up for someone unable to speak up for themselves. I was proud to defend her and take on my position equals. It felt great and I'd do it 100 times over.
Deb1: How social attitudes, political views, economic status, and personal beliefs and views impact and/or influence our choosing in certain circumstances (such as when we have power over a situation or the power to give and take away), and our overall views.
Deb2: Probably. I remember a positive event so I think I was likely a bit less cynical than had I recalled a time I did not use my authoritative power for better. Whereas had I recalled a negative time, I would most likely  have been a bit harsh in my responses. I do not think it would have been much different in my case because I seem to be able to keep my emotions separate from most endeavors like this. But I can see how someone might think of a bad time, have to write about it and then afterwards their responses being a bit narrow-mined. I hope that makes sense.
Deb3: Thank you for making it interesting and I hope your research goes well.

Essay: I worked as a copywriter for a rental company. I got along well with my boss. He was friendly and considerate. Then all of the sudden he called me one day and laid me off without any notice. Then he ignored my calls and texts about getting my last paycheck. I tried to get in touch with him for months and he ignored me. It made me incredibly angry. I felt betrayed and taken advantage of. It was really hard for me to let it go and move on.
Deb1: How we perceive emotion through memory and sight and how those emotions affect our own emotions as they are perceived.
Deb2: Yes. It caused me to feel more awake because I remembered how angry I was when it happened.

Essay: Last week I was evaluated by my supervisor.  I felt very nervous as I had missed a lot of work due to illness and my car breaking down and my child ending up in the hospital.  I felt like I was speculated as being lazy.  I felt very insecure and had no power or control over how she felt about how I was managing my time
Deb1: How much we give back to others based on our feelings
Deb2: No

Essay: When I was a sophomore in high school, I was a platoon leader for cadet corps. Deb2: No

Essay: When my mother passed away, my brother had power over the situation. And he was in control of how or who her money was to be given out or given too. And of course he gave all the money to his self. I didn't get any of the money. instead he gave me what items I wanted out of her house.
Deb1: I think its about how I think about other people, their nationality, etc. You want to see if I think that I am better than other people. race or religion.

Essay: My sister had some money she owed me. I went over to her house to get it, and she claimed she didn't have it. I walked in the house, and talked to her about it. Essay: I have had power in few circumstances. One of those times was when I was directing a play I wrote in high school. I had many situations in which I had power over others. I had complete power to decide whether I liked their ideas.

Essay: Last month I was holding interviews for two open positions. I was given total liberty in who I chose for each position. One girl came in over dressed, green dress and cheetah heels with way too much perfume. Right off the bat I didn't want to hire her because of her appearance.
Deb1: Perception of self , financially how well off you are and your character from your point of view

Essay: The woman was my supervisor and told me she would write me up because I went to the bathroom before clocking out, even though I had been holding it for the last half hour of my shift. I felt she was being a bitch, and I was very angry.

Essay: Honestly, I can't really think of a time when I had power over someone! I'm a housewife so I am not in work-related situations and I love and adore my husband so I try not to usurp "power" over him. I hope this doesn't get me disqualified!
Deb1: Something about personality and political views
Deb2: Nope! It's effect was that while I am in control of my life, I do not abuse power by any means.
Deb3: I could go either way with relaxing or working out! Wasn't sure how to answer! A nap would be lovely, but if a friend came along I'd love to work our with her!

Essay: I was working at the mall. I had a boss who had power over how I did my job which was to make sure all the stock was on the shelves. He was very particular about how he wanted things to be put on the shelves. He was very annoying and it was frustrating that he had such power over me.

Essay: A previous boss of mine that had control over me. I worked 9-5 and I was on call 24/7. I was exhausted. I was only being paid for my 9-5 hours and not for the endless calls and staffing I had to provide 24/7. I approached my boss and asked for a raise or to be compensated for some of the hours I was working on my own time. My boss instantly became angry and began pounding her fists on my desk and screaming in my face. I felt confessed, hurt and angry because of her reaction. I felt as if I was working so hard and only asking for what I deserved. I felt attacked in such an unprofessional way. I felt as if she had control over me because I needed my job and had to pay my bills. After several minutes of her screaming and pounding her fists on my desk, I couldn't take anymore. I gathered personal belongings and I stood up with tears in my eyes and she asked me "are you leaving?". I responded in a calm voice " Yes, yes I am leaving. You cannot treat me like this anymore. I have spent the past two years running your company and I do not deserve to be verbally attacked anymore." I walked out the door and left. Still feeling very upset and shaken.
Deb1: How people feel when they are not in control, their emotions and feelings.
Deb2: No, I do not believe so.

Essay: I had my annual evaluation at work and prior to meeting with my supervisor, I was instructed to complete a self evaluation, rating how well my performance was. I did and when I sat down to meet with my supervisor, she discussed my performance and praised me for being such a great employee. Although I felt like I was in the position to get a high rating score and therefore receive a raise (promotion), I did not. I didn't understand how she would increase my rating if she believed that I have been doing such a great job. I felt defeated and cheated because here is this woman who is "in charge of me and had the power over the amount of salary." It was demeaning and honestly felt a slave for a corporation who acknowledged my hard work but yet did not want to award me as such. It didn't make me feel good at all.
Deb1: The purpose of the study was to rate people's emotions caused by certain circumstances
Deb2: No, I don't believe at all.
Deb3: Great study! I look forward to more.

Essay: I was a United States Marine I weighed 145 pounds, and I was fantastic at my job. For two years I tried to get a promotion, but my superiors did not like me I didn't fit in I asked questions I followed orders but I was a great athlete every day I was hazed until I started to question my sanity and my right to live. I never got promoted, and I was barely able to hang on to an honorable discharge. For two years after that, I couldn't sleep, had nightmares and could barely function. I can still see their faces  any time I close my eyes or get upset. It feels like there is an elephant sitting on my chest and it takes every ounce of self-control I have not to panic there are still days where I wish I would have died.
Deb1: How people's​ experiences in the past shape their view of the present. How their experiences become the lens with which they view the world.
Deb2: Fresh painful experiences always have a negative correlation on an individual's​ ability to interpret people expressions and actions.

Essay: I was in a domestic violence situation,  and my boyfriend, at the time, had control of all the money that came into our household. I lost my job behind him and that gave him more power over me. I hate him. If he was here right now, I think I would spit in his face.
Deb1: to find out about people and relationships to things
Deb2: No, not at all. I am still believing in love and happily ever after. He only tainted me for not doing my background check on a guy. I also allowed him to move in very quickly after coming off a broken heart.

Essay: First time I hired an employee. I was extremely nervous as to whether I was hiring the right person
Deb1: social perceptions
Deb2: none

Essay: My kids got gift cards for christmas. I had to help them choose what they wanted to use their gift cards to buy. One of them wanted something that cost more than what their gift card was for. I felt bad because I didn't have the money to cover the difference. I ended up convincing them to get something else that they had enough money to buy. They ended up being happy with what they got, but still wanted the other item too. I felt bad because I could not get them the item they really wanted because I did not have enough money.
Deb1: To see how people feel about themselves and others around them.
Deb2: No, I do not believe my essay had any effect on the answers to this study.
Deb3: No, I believe it was a good study.

Essay: I was Shift supervisor at a Starbucks, I made the schedules,had to write up complaints on employees,etc, It was a very hard job, didnt enjoy writing people up and writing discipline reports on them
Deb1: I think it was to see where others heads are at. How compassionate you are and what your values are
Deb2: No, I dont think it affected anything

Essay: As a teacher, I am routinely evaluated several times each school year.  My job and salary depend on my evaluator's impression of my teaching during his evaluation visits.   /  / My last evaluation was in November.  My evaluator joined a class that is typically very noisy, although hard-working.  I was extremely nervous at first.  It was horrible to know that, no matter how good my lesson was, if my students were uncooperative, that could have repercussions on my paycheck.  Strangely enough, the day that he joined our class, my students were all mysteriously silent and focused.  I was incredibly relieved that they seemed to know how important it was for my career to leave my evaluator with a good impression.  We sailed through the class, with only one minor discipline issue, which my evaluator later said he thought I had handled very well.  I was thrilled when the bell rang and my students and my evaluator all left my room.
Deb1: Recalling a time when you are out of power, and then reacting to facial gestures?  Perhaps people will all look uneasy if we ourselves describe a time when we were out of power?
Deb2: My experience wasn't entirely negative, but many of the facial gestures seemed negative.

Essay: I was accused of stealing money from a job I previously held. The manager hadn't even looked for the missing cash in the drop safe and had not looked at the camera footage from the night before. Another employee behind me was in charge of checking the safe. Upon being accused and asking if they had proof they said they just couldn't find it. So, I gathered a bunch of pictures on my phone of health code violations. I reported them to the health department and then the next day they somehow "found" the missing money accounted for. I felt amazing after I successfully pulled a power play and got my crooked manager to basically admit that he was skimming from his parent's business.
Deb1: I think the purpose of this study is to understand how experiences (education, race, gender etc.) influence personality.
Deb2: No.

Essay: I was the manager of a small company. I had 5 employees who answered to me. I enjoyed being in control of the daily operations and I liked that my employees respected me. I tried to always be a fair and respectful boss.
Deb1: To see how a person would delegate the tickets after thinking of being in a position of power
Deb2: No, not really

Essay: The situation was at my last job, and my boss was my uncle and he used his relation to me to pressure me into staying after hours to help a coworker finish their work. I felt especially used because my uncle's son also worked with us and I thought that he would ask his son first, but he only asked me.
Deb1: I think the purpose of this study would be to see how people acted if they are slightly bothered and how they perceive the world and people around them.
Deb2: I think it affected how many raffle tickets I gave because I was much more generous than normally.
Deb3: I like how there was the visualization and raffle ticket parts of the study to try to put the person completing the study in a desired mindframe.

Essay: I am the President of a youth sports program.  There was a time when a parent cornered me up against a building, demanding that his child get more playing time and he threatened bodily harm if I didn't do something about it.  I was very scared.
Deb1: How people may or may not perceive certain emotions.

Essay: When I'm teaching private instrument lessons to my students. I have all of the information that they want, and they have to listen to me to get that information. Essay: Working at my last job, my supervisor had power over me. She would make me feel incompetent at my job every day and would push the dirty work onto me. It made me feel angry and sometimes depressed. It made me feel as if I was worth less than she was.

Essay: I had power over someone when they came to me to do their nails while I was in school and they wanted fancy Halloween designs. I had the power to try my best and do what they wanted, or to simply tell them that because I was a student I had not learned how to do that yet. I decided to go ahead and try my best and give them what they wanted. I was scared and nervous. I had never done nails so detailed before and I was worried that I would not be able to do them. I did my very best on the one hand and she loved them. So I was relieved about that, but then I got nervous again. What if I could not do the second hand as well as the first. There was only one way to find out. So I jumped in and did her second hand. It was slightly harder and I felt more presser because I had set a certain precedence with the first hand. The second hand turned out just as great as the first hand though. So I gave her what she wanted and it made me feel good and boosted my confidence in myself.
Deb1: The purpose of this study was to determine how people perceive themselves.
Deb2: Yes. I think it made me feel good remembering and made me answer more confidentiality

Essay: I was in a job position where I had a chance for a promotion, but it was only up to another person in management to be able to allow me to reach my goal of a promotion. It was an incredibly helpless feeling knowing that my financial stability was based on one person who had complete control of the situation. The news of the promotion would not come until later in the week, so it was stressful everyday wondering what my fate would be within that company.
Deb1: To show what people think of themselves and how trusting they are of others. /

Essay: I was the lead on a work assignment, and I had an individual working directly under me.  The normal "end of work" time came, and the individual wanted to leave.  However I did not think the assignment had been completed satisfactorily.  So I told the individual that they could not leave until all parameters of the work assignment were completed satisfactorily.  The individual was not happy about this, but they did comply.  I was not happy about the situation, but the work had to be done.  I felt good when the individual listened to me, and when we completed the assignment.
Deb1: I assume the purpose of this study is to see how individuals perceive people around them.  Especially when in close proximity to them, by examining how they interpret body language.

Essay: Being disciplined as a child, I mostly felt as though my father had power over me and I could not talk back or do anything against his will.

I get paid the most out of aome employees, i work minimal days and i get vacations like i need. In a way, i had gotten what i wanted.

Deb2: Yea it did. It showed that if someone really wants to keep you, theyll do anything to make you stay.

Essay: I was being interviewed by a nurse in a doctor's office in the small town where I live. Because I live in a very small town in the middle of nowhere, with no other doctor's or nurses, I had to speak to this woman. She was an old woman, with brown eyes, shoulder length white hair that had some curl to it, a soft round face and was prone to wearing sweaters and such. She thought of herself as professional but was very close-minded and insulted both my mother and myself for life decisions that were long ago made, we no longer had any control over and are not objectionable by any mores society has held for thirty years. I wanted to punch her in the face and call her names for attempting to make my mother feel small and worthless, but I sat there and took it because I needed to see a doctor and there were no other service providers who would take someone without insurance.
Deb1: Attitudes towards racism and class
Deb2: I don't think it particularly affected me. I was already pretty beat before the study and the situation I described had nothing to do with class or racism.

Essay: It was a situation at a previous job in which something had gone wrong and in order for me to fix it and maintain employment, I had to do a certain task (non-sexual) for it. It was a task that I absolutely did not want to do and it felt like being sentenced to detention when you are in middle or high school. Other emotions that come to mind are a lack of control of your environment.
Deb1: I think the study wants to see how we measure trust in other people based on our own self-declared socioeconomic status. But the other questions about a lack of power and the eyes dont seem to point in that direction. How we perceive our own experiences, the facial expressions of others, the dynamics of trust between various groups of people, and our socioeconomic status all are tied together in this study. However what it means, I dont know.
Deb2: The essay in the beginning? I think it put me on edge for the rest of the test. It removed barriers that may have prevented me from answering the questions with 100% honesty.

Essay: My first job interview right out of high school! I needed the job very much and the gentle man doing the interview was not interested because he thought I didn't need it because of several reasons. I lived at home with my parents, they both worked, I paid them no rent , I had no experience, there were plenty of people needing work that he didn't need to hire me and he just kept telling me these things over and over. I told him that the only way that I could get experience was to get the job so I could begin to earn experience, I was more qualified than most of the other people needing the job, I wanted to get out on my own and not continue to live off of my parents. I also told him that I needed to pay bills just like all the Moms and Dads that wanted this job. I felt very small and inadequate when I was sitting there. I knew that I deserved this job just like everybody else that was applying and I was being looked at like I was a spoiled child living off of my parents. Which was not true at all my parents had good jobs, but they did not just hand anything to us! We had to work for everything!! When I left the interview I stood up and told this man that he was unfair about the fact that I would be fine not getting the job because I had my parents to fall back on! I would have been an asset to his company and he was making a mistake by not hiring me! I didn't have my parents to fall back on and I would have a job by the end of the month because I was not letting my parents pay my bills that was not how I was raised!! I was very mad when I left there and very hurt and he made me feel very small and inadequate. I did get a job by month end and it was a better one than he was offering too.
Deb1: To figure out why we feel the way we do in a situation and what makes us work that way
Deb2: yes, I was more in tune with how I feel
Deb3: I did enjoy the survey and it did get me to thinking about my feelings

Essay: Arguing with step-dad the coffee breath and no shirt standout it. arguing about him smoking and he had become hostile standing up towering over me. i felt threatened but firm in my opinion. like a David and Goliath situation. telling him to stop was hard felt conflicted as to keep yelling or just shut up felt like i could accomplish something but he did have power over me but i felt i needed to overcome it for this situation.

The project manager was really helpless, since it was depending on me, and he was one who will be beaten in case if we do not fixit asap. Essay: I had a job interview about 2 months ago, everything went well. During that week I was schedule for a physical, so basically I got the job I just had to go to my appointment. I went to the appointment and the  receptionist told me that I missed it. I said "No that can't be right". I went down to the office were I was interviewed and the person that interviewed me was on a lunch break. I spoke to another person "in charge" and she told me "usually people who don't show or miss an appointment, will be marked as a no show". My appointment was scheduled two days before. The crazy thing is that when I went to my physical(the missed appointment), that was the same date and time as my interview from the previous week. I got the interview mixed up with my physical date. That lady had so much power because a person that offers you a job is basically in control of your finances and I was also enrolled in school and I just wish I had power over my own finances. She made me feel very little, because the least I did was show up. If I didn't show up at all then that's when they should have went on about their lives. I'll be a doctor at that hospital while their still working there, and I'll say "Oh, I remember when you didn't offer me that job".
Deb1: I've been asked so many times by teachers/professors "how much money would you give, if you had this much and it paid off tuition, utility bills, etc" I would always say all of it or most of it because I do not like to fall in the tricks of teachers/professors. In high school I was asked this in my economics class and in college I was asked this in my sociology class and I believe my psyc class also. This is definitely some type of social experiment based on race, income, gender, etc. Nice survey.
Deb2: Definitely, as a minority I feel at the bottom of the ladder, based on my race, occupation, sometimes gender, and education. Nice survey, I see what you did there.
Deb3: Good study, I would participate in more like these.

Essay: When I was a kid, my sister was babysitting for two boys, who stayed at our house for the summer during the day.  One day, one of the kids was in my bedroom, even though he knew I didn't want him there.  When I told him to get out, he didn't listen to me.  So, I dug the fingernails of one of my hands into his back and shoved him out of the room.  I felt momentarily justified, but then got confused when he started crying.  Then, I got scared because I was worried that I'd be in trouble with my parents.
Deb1: To determine how people feel after they've recalled an experience where they were powerful.  Also, to see how generous they are they after recalling such an event.  Also, trying to correlate it how well people read facial expressions and where they see themselves in society.
Deb2: Yes, because the only example I could think of was one that led to me feeling bad as a child.  As an adult, I don't try to exert force over other people because I'm not good at it.

Essay: I was working an in-office contract job, and it was time to renegotiate my contract. I met with my boss to negotiate terms, and he had made certain oral promises in the time leading up. At that time, he then reneged on his promises and expected me to sign a contract for less than I was asking for. It was a difficult position because I had financial obligations that prevented me from walking away entirely.
Deb1: Determine how trusting I am when given the choice of helping an other.
Deb2: no

Essay: Working in retail, I was a head cashier able to process returns. We had a customer who was a 'repeat offender' who would come in multiple times a week with coupons and returns and new purchases that cheated or took advantage of our return policy. After many encounters with her my manager had given me permission to refuse service to her. The customer was completely flabbergasted that her scheme was no longer going to be allowed. It felt great knowing that I no longer had to deal with her antics. She was infuriated and irate, but I simply denied her service and it felt wonderful.
Deb1: determining how people perceive themselves as opposed to others based on certain qualities
Deb2: not much but it made the survey seem interesting
Deb3: the eye pictures seemed familiar, one looked like chris evans and one looked like donald trump for sure

Essay: My son wanted a soccer ball, and i told him he needed to earn it throught doing his chores. He was upset that I wouldnt buy it for him right now! He had a tempertantrum. I was embarrassed and upset with him for acting like he was 5 when he was 8 at the time. All he had to do was make his bed n put dishes in dishwasher n take trash out for a week. Sounded reasonable to me . He just couldnt handle the thought of not wanting to wait.
Deb1: Dont know
Deb2: No none

Essay: The first time I allowed my now husband to kiss me was electric. It was our first date. He took me to a Detroit Tigers baseball game. After the game we walked past a beautiful old church. We tried to go inside but the doors were locked. As we stood on the sidewalk outside the church, I was nervous. Although the city was thronging that afternoon with cars and crowds of people leaving the game, I suddenly felt like we were the only two people in Detroit. I knew he wanted to kiss me but he was not going to force it. It was up to me. I turned my face up to him and parted my lips slightly. He leaned in and kissed me. The noise of the cars and the crowd completely disappeared. When we pulled apart, the world came crashing back around us, though nobody seemed to notice that monumental moment for two lovers.
Deb1: I think the purpose of the study may be to gauge perspective on how people make judgments about others, and if those judgments are influenced by social status and ethnicity.
Deb2: I don't think that it affected me significantly but if there was an affect, it was a positive one, in that it might have helped me feel a certain amount of warmth towards others. It was a happy memory of romantic love.
Deb3: It was interesting. I'd love to know what the eyes were really "saying." A few of the options seemed to me to be conveying joy, but the selections were all negative. I hope I'm not that bad at judging other's emotions!

Essay: The situation involved my desire for a direct monetary raise instead of compensation through other means for a newly acquired position. I gathered information for how much extra time was spent doing tasks for this new position, which was in addition to current role obligations. I presented this information and was told yes, it would go forward with Human Resources. However, this never occurred despite reminders. I felt highly annoyed and frustrated that I couldn't change the compensation for the leadership role acquired. I even went as far as to request this raise for the person who will be taking the role for the following year where I wouldn't get this compensation because I believed very strongly in it.
Deb1: Purpose is to evaluate trust levels of others when they have the power over you. For example, I gave the person 1000 tickets because logically, we could both come out ahead by splitting 1500 each compared to me keeping 1000 tickets. However, the person could keep all 3000 for which I would decrease my trust in others for future transactions.
Deb2: A little bit. It should have affected it more.

Essay: The situation I had power in was last year in my final year of high school, for the final the teacher had the students as a class grade each others finals, after a student presented the project that was their final. Each person seemed nervous since every other student determined the grade of the biggest portion of the class. I felt bad for nearly everybody that presented at gave them a decent grade mostly due to the fact I wanted to receive a good grade as well.

Deb2: no

Essay: I was interviewing a person for a position we had open at our company.  I could tell the person was well qualified for the position, but also nervous about the interview and wanted to make a good impression.  I felt like putting the applicant at ease and allowing them the opportunity to tell me why they would be good for the job.

Essay: I had hired some very cheap laborers to paint my house.  To be invited back a second day to work each had to work very hard, quickly, and with good quality.  This was hard work that involved using ladders, and i could tell that they worked harder when they knew i was watching.  I felt a little quilty, having control over how much effort they put in, knowing that if i stood there by their ladders they would be under far more stress, but also wold get my job done faster.
Deb1: to see how much different groups of people trust others
Deb2: not really.  i don't think it affected me.
Deb3: had trouble with the ladder question.  while i associate more money and higher education with high social status, i tend to think that having a particular job doesn't relate.  social status is enjoyed by the people with time and flexibility to enjoy it-  not people who work 100 hours a week, despite how well paid or educated.

Essay: I was the only one in a situation at work who knew how to proceed with proper process.  I had to direct others on what to do and how to do it.  I felt resentful that those who make more than me did not know what to do.  However, I also felt proud that I did know what to do and how to help my subordinates.

Deb2: Not really thinking back on that experience was pretty compartmentalized in my mind..

Essay: I was managing a summer restaurant several years ago.  During a very busy day, an employee asked to leave early to attend a graduation party.  I remember the person looking a bit anxious or embarrassed to be asking on such short notice.  While I knew we would be left very shorthanded, I let the person leave early.  While I knew it may not have been the best business decision at the moment, I based my decision on the person's history as far as reliability and attitude, both of which were very good.

Deb2: I thought of my essay when answering the questions about empathizing with others.  I think my answers were similar to my response in the essay.

Essay: Planning a concert for my college, along with another school, was a nightmare and she was the Freddy Kruger of all of my ideas. Blonde hair and hazel eyes never made me so angry before. She had all of the control even though we were on the same level of authority. I still don't understand why she got to choose. I have never hated anyone until I met her. She's pushy. She bullied everyone into agreeing with her and I was the only one who saw right through her. I'm still pissed off about it. Salt residue.

Essay: I am the coordinator for a volunteer program. One of my volunteers needed me to sign a paper certifying she had completed a certain number of hours. However, she had failed to show up to her assigned shift three times and had only volunteered once in a six month period. She was frustrated about this, as was I, but I told her explicitly that she would not receive credit for her unexcused absences. I also referred her to the program's list of volunteer responsibilities and policies. I also cautioned her about having unexcused absences in the next six-month period.
Deb1: To understand people's perceptions of others.
Deb2: No, I don't think it affected anything

Essay: One of my co-workers position had just been eliminated at work, and her former responsibilities fell on me. I felt that my position should be re-graded based on the new workload. I went to upper management with my request and the VP was the one I needed to convince. She had the power to have the compensation group re-evaluate my job for a raise. I felt very nervous and afraid because I thought that they might fire me too for my demands. I also felt a bit resentful that I had to be the one to bring it up... why didn't the management see this as being unfair and request this without my prodding? I sat in the VP's office and tried not to show my nerves and also tried very hard to control my voice so that I didn't come across whiny or demanding. She nodded along as I spoke and I remember her eyes showing sympathy, so I did believe she saw my point. The rest of her body language was more authoritative, though, with her almost seeming to tower over me as she sat rigid across the desk. So even though I felt some sympathy, I was still very intimidated and didn't know if it was for show or not. I did end up getting my position re-evaluated, but it took a year of begging.
Deb1: Understanding how people interpret emotions when they feel upset or overpowered
Deb2: I don't know if it affected my answers, but my mood wasn't very positive after recalling the situation I wrote about.

Essay: When my boyfriend and I argue I feel as If I am the one who has the power to fix things or to continue being mad. He did something in the past so those are the consequences. When we fight I feel powerful. If I try to break up with him he will do everything possible to fix things up. Deep down I feel good because I know I am in control. Deb1: To evaluate attitudes about others & to see if people trust others.

Essay: Employee evaluation and we were in the office and he told me what his thoughts were of my work and I felt like i didnt have an opinion.

Essay: Post surgery...a nurse over medicated me....rather than call for help...she violently shook me, causing injury to my surgical wound, and traumatizing me forever. I felt scared, because I could not fight back.....and she smiled....
Deb1: Well, I figure because you initially began by the participant remembering a negative thought....it would seem that there is a correlation between events happening towards an individual and how they perceive themselves on a personal/emotional level, and also how they perceive themselves within society as a whole possibly because of those events that they had no control over.
Deb2: No, but is interesting looking back, thinking that even events that has happened years ago, could still be fresh in ones mind, and evoke emotions so raw.
Deb3: Thank you, I think surveys like this actually can be helpful to the individual taking it if they are open to a deeper level of understanding and consciousness.

Essay: I was helping to give a middle school student a very important test orally. She had a learning disability and sometimes acted a little less mature than her peers. Therefore, she was frequently asking me to give her the answers or for a hint. I had the power to push her toward the correct answers. She wanted to do well and I could make that happen. I felt empowered. I felt pressure. I felt like I need to do the right thing.
Deb1: My best guess would be that the study's purpose is to show the relationship between an individual's trust in others, ideas about well-being/security and risk-taking.
Deb2: No, I didn't think that it did. There is a slight possibility that my essay/visualization session caused me to think of myself as very privileged... compared to how I would normally view myself. I have seen something similar to that "rungs on a ladder" question... and I would usually rate myself lower on the ladder. But this time, I was thinking about the vast majority of people who don't have the opportunities that have been afforded to me.
Deb3: This got me thinking. Very interesting.

Essay: I was in charge of a small group of peopleon a volunteer trip. We had to bring things in from one area on site tothe other and organize it. I felt helpful and empowered.
Deb1: To understand motives for decisions making generosity verus greed
Deb2: I think it made me more cofident in my decision making

Essay: I was a bit of a juvenile delinquent when I was younger. I had a probation officer who had significant authority over whether my CHINS could stop and I could be out of the court system. She was really flirty with all the officers and dressed inappropriately for her job. Her name was Theresa and though most people said she was a bitch I didn't mind her, she was pretty fair with me and allowed my chins to end at the appropriate time.
Deb1: Some sort of sociological study, not sure.
Deb2: No.

Essay: My ex girlfriend had power over me - she was or is undiagnosed borderline personality disorder. The relationship started out fast and furious and then after I moved in with her she had some rage episodes. One time she was threatening suicide, screaming, throwing, biting, scratching, all in an effort to get me to admit to something I didn't do. I was in a bad situation because there was no where to go and no way to make her see reason. I gave her power over me that time. That experience was undeniably intense. I was scared, crying, loaded with adrenaline, yet I didn't do anything but let her rage. It was a scary, traumatic experience.
Deb1: Test my feelings and trust level after describing a situation in which someone else had control over me. Then see how I interpreted the look in someone's eyes under the same residual feeling and how I was feeling afterward. Also the raffle tickets could be an indication of the level of trust.
Deb2: Yes, as it made me recall a traumatic experience, I think it affected my immediate feelings regarding trust. My original intention was to give 1000 tickets to the other, thinking they'd split and we'd each have 1500 - but then I started to doubt and wondered why they wouldn't just keep all 3000 and not give me any. I think that doubt crept in due to recalling what I described in the essay.

Essay: My first job at JCPenny's I had a supervisor a man with white hair, glasses, and about 60 years old that had power over me whether if i would keep the job or not. I loved that job but I did not know you are on a 3 month probationary period for the first 3 months you work there. At the end of the 3 months they said they were letting me go and didn't give me any reason. I felt devastated. I loved that job. I had a really good time working there and I was good at my job.
Deb1: Sociology study to understand about peoples beliefs and thoughts.
Deb2: No
Deb3: Trust is based on what peoples actions portray in everyday life. It is earned on something just given out.

Essay: I had been tracking my grades in a math class on a spreadsheet and at the end of the semester, my grade and the grade my teacher had did not match. I had to schedule a meeting with her to find out why she gave me a lower grade than expected and I was very nervous. She had me sit in her desk chair, and looked over her records with me and it turned out I had written one assignment's grade down wrong. I was SO embarrassed to have made a simple math problem and not caught it. I apologized. She was usually a very strict teacher but she actually gave me the higher grade in the end.
Deb1: To see if people of a political persuasion are more or less generous?
Deb2: It might have! It was a time when someone helped me.

Essay: The situation i thought of was at my job, i was the person under the big boss. I made most of the big decisions, did the hiring and firing of people, reprimanded them when necessary. That's the power position that came to mind. At time is was hard position to be in, but it did have its perks.
Deb1: To get an idea of where people are in society compared  to how they interact with others, and how they feel about them.
Deb2: No

Essay: I was the lead staff at an agency charged to manage a multi-million grant funding program that our county was awarded for an initial number of years.  Our county was excited for the many benefits children were going to receive in form of educational and social services. The initial pilot year, many organizations - large and very small - qualified if they served this population. Everyone wanted the opportunity to obtain funding. We made every effort to reach out to all areas of the county, use various marketing methods, build partnerships to help us get the word out, offer informational workshops and trainings at various hours, locations and days plus make them available in multiple languages. We also accepted handwritten grant proposals. It felt good to be part of solutions and positive impact in the community - specific to doing good for children.
Deb1: Generate political inferences based on how we view others, view others as a reflection of ourselves... and what may attribute to those views.
Deb2: Yes, perhaps the words chosen to describe the experience or the lens used to describe it.
Deb3: The exposure to many different types of people, cultures, religions while growing up - in college - and a little travel helped in expanding views of others and the world. Growing up in poverty also empowered me to view the value in opportunities others shared or made available.

Essay: The only thing that I can really think of is that when I was younger, I was a server. The restaurant that I managed/served at was closing it's doors forever, and it was our last night. Everyone was drinking and dancing, we had sold out of most of the food, and even the help was pleasantly buzzed. Some people came in who had wronged me in the past; just awful people. I got to decide whether to serve them or to ignore them and be rude. Given that I wasn't about to be fired on my last night, I chose to ignore them and not let them ruin my last evening there.

Essay: I felt like I wanted to get around him.

I could not wait to get it over with.  I some how managed to pass and was promoted to Sergeant.

Essay: In this specific situation I had power over a close friend while we playing a recreational sport. I was winning and had power over the game. During this situation I felt excited, and was enjoying it. On the other hand however, I felt bad for my friend since they seemed disheartened by their lost power.

Essay: A few of my friends had moved in with me a while back and after a week of complaining about nobody helping me out, I got angry and yelled at them all. Essay: A colleague at work picked up a shift for me therefor he had some power over me. I did not like the feeling of knowing I owed him a favor or shift. It made me feel like I was below him. After I paid him back I felt a weight lift off of my shoulders.

Essay: I was at work, taking a phone call from my mother. For some reason, I got a little homesick, stressed out, and upset during our phone call. She continued to belittle me and abuse her power over me. I got fed up and walked out of the door. I have never felt that unsafe in my life.

Essay: I was a manager evaluating the performance of one of my direct reports. There were some good things in the report but also some difficult things to share. During the course of the conversation, the employee was at first defensive and resistant to guidance.  But as we talked, this person was more open to changing how they approached similar situations.

Essay: I once had a manager, little turd of a man.  He drew on his hair with an eyeliner pen.  And he hated me because I wasn't black. Essay: Everyday at my job i am in a position of power. The one day i am thinking about was regarding a staff being mandated to stay for another shift. I explained to the staff that it was their turn. They became very upset by it, and i truly felt bad for them as it was going to be a twenty hour shift. She began to cry and say that she wasn't sure she could handle it. She was a very new and young staff and had never had to work such a long shift in her entire life. After a few minutes i was able to make some phone calls to get another staff to come in and relieve her early. Although she still had to work 16 hours, it was better than 20.  I felt good that i was able to help her, and bad that she had to stay all at the same time.

Essay: After marriage, we had a situation, when I had to make a decision for our family on whether to migrate to a different location or not. Essay: At a job interview, the interview was going and I felt that it was a sure sign of my getting the job. However, when I was open about  my mental illness I felt the mood in the room change. It made me feel very uncomfortable.

Essay: In this incident, I was working as a supervisor for a crew of low-income high school students on a 6 week summer job program. /  / In this particular moment, several of them had asked me if I could pick them up in the morning (with the van we used every day on the job).  I told them no, because it was against policy.   The policy was that the participants arrive on their own to a daily meeting site.   /  / I'd felt defensive, because I cared for them and their ability to arrive on time to work and I knew they might not always have bus money or that their parents' may not be available, yet I saw picking each up as an extra burden on the responsibilities I had to exercise each day--and it was against policy.
Deb1: The purpose of the study seems to examine ties between empathy and social status.
Deb2: Not really, no.
Deb3: Very interesting.  I myself am interested in studying how empathy is built through the sharing of personal narrative.

Essay: On a recent vacation with my family we were without a car.  We were told by a family member than we did not need to hire a car as they would be more than happy to take us anywhere we needed on go.  We therefore needed to rely on this family member to take us to our destinations.  On one occasion we were looking to go somewhere and they stated they were unable to take us due to changes in their plans.  I felt completely out of my comfort zone as I do not usually rely on people but they had complete control over when we would be doing and it did not make me feel comfortable and it made me angry that I had not made alternative arrangements.
Deb1: Trust
Deb2: Made me think if i really thought about the situation from their point of view.

Essay: During college, I had a part time office job at a very small interior design company.  After a few months of working there, the owner of the company (twice my age), cornered me in a small copy room while I was making copies, held me against the machine and tried to kiss me.  I managed to leave the room, but was extremely uncomfortable and couldn't tell anyone..He was the owner of a tiny firm of 3 people, plus the secretary and myself. I just quit the job, never returned.  I was angry and sad and disappointed. I felt powerless to complain to anyone..there was no HR department, etc. Plus, it was a Japanese firm, so there was also a cultural and language barrier.
Deb1: How people's experiences, perceptions, and basic personality are related.  If I wasn't so tired right now, I'd be able to write more!
Deb2: An essay?  I assume this means the experience where I felt someone had power over me.   I could be wrong, but I don't think describing that experience affected the rest of my answers.
Deb3: It was interesting, I enjoyed participating.

Essay: I was the Supervisor, and I had control to approve or disapprove time off requests.  the specific event visualized was with an employee that I had to deny their request due to operational restrictions.   i felt very pooly about the situation, but was obligated to uphold operational statuses of the company.
Deb1: Understanding empathy.

Essay: My wife and I had applied for a home loan with a financer from our bank that we have an account with. We had a scheduled meeting with the gentleman a week after we inquired about it. There was a lot of feelings of anxiety leading up to our appointment. /  / We discussed our financial situation, wages, job positions, hours worked, other property we may own, any savings or retirement plans.  He evaluated us based on our total income and deducted our expenses to figure out what our disposable income was. My wife and I were very stressed at this point due to the man having all the power to control whether we are able to start building a home for our family or to continue to struggle with a temporary residence. /  / After he took everything into consideration, he opted to not provide us with the loan due to having a short, limited credit history. The feeling of disappointment was enormous at this point. I felt ashamed that regardless of the hard work we put forth, it wasn't enough. We had both been very upset over the outcome of the meeting but we had decided to do what we had been doing all along, work hard, so that eventually we would receive a home loan decision in our favor.
Deb1: A study on how people feel about themselves objectively.
Deb2: No
Deb3: It is interesting to be asked to write about a vulnerable situation I was in. Usually people like to forget uncomfortable situations and only focus on positive things.

Essay: I interviewed to get accepted into a physical education program. I was turned down due to a disability known as a hearing loss. I had hearing aids but that was not acceptable.  My whole future was gone at that moment.
